# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australian-football-harmony-cup
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Albania was inhabited by several Illyrian tribes, among them the Ardiaei, Bylliones, Dassaretii, Enchele, and Taulantians, with the Chaonians settled in the southwest.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Several colonies were founded by the Ancient Greeks along the Albanian coast, most notably Apollonia.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The Illyrians were the dominant power in Albania before the rise of Macedon.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Following the Illyrian Wars, Albania was integrated into the Roman Empire and remained in the Byzantine Empire after its partition.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] During the Middle Ages, several Albanian principalities emerged, most notably the Principality of Arbanon, Kingdom of Albania, Principality of Albania and Albania Veneta.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] In the 15th century, Albania became a center of resistance against Ottoman expansion under the leadership of Gjergj Kastrioti Skanderbeg, whose military campaigns repelled Ottoman advances for over two decades.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Although incorporated into the Ottoman Empire, Albania retained distinct cultural and social identities throughout four centuries of foreign rule, culminating in the Albanian Renaissance in the 19th century.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Albania declared independence in 1912, followed by a turbulent 20th century marked by monarchy, foreign occupation during both World Wars, and a communist regime under Enver Hoxha.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Since its independence in 1912, Albania has undergone a number of political changes, transitioning from a monarchy to a communist regime before becoming a sovereign parliamentary constitutional republic.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Governed by a constitution prioritising the separation of powers, the country's political structure includes a parliament, a ceremonial president, a functional prime minister and a hierarchy of courts.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Albania is a developing country with an upper-middle income economy driven by the service sector, with manufacturing and tourism, which attracted over 11 million visitors in 2024, also playing significant roles.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The illegal drug trade in Albania contributes around US$100 million to the economy per year.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] After the dissolution of its communist system, the country shifted from centralised planning to an open market economy.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Albanian citizens have universal health care access and free primary and secondary education.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The country is an official candidate for membership in the European Union, and has been negotiating accession since 2022.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The origin of the name "Albania" can be traced back to medieval Latin and the association with the Illyrian tribe of the Albani.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] This connection is further supported by the writings of the Ancient Greek geographer Ptolemy during the 2nd century AD, where he included the settlement of Albanopolis situated to the northeast of Durrës.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The presence of a medieval settlement named Albanon or Arbanon hints at the possibility of historical continuity.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The precise relationship between these historical references and the question of whether Albanopolis was synonymous with Albanon remain subjects of scholarly debate.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The Byzantine historian Michael Attaliates, in his 11th-century historical account, provides the earliest undisputed reference to the Albanians, when he mentions them as participants in a revolt against Constantinople in 1079.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] He also identifies the Arbanitai as subjects of the Duke of Dyrrachium.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] In the Middle Ages, Albania was denoted as *Arbëri* or *Arbëni* by its inhabitants, who identified themselves as *Arbëreshë* or *Arbëneshë*.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Albanians employ the terms *Shqipëri* or *Shqipëria* for their nation, designations that trace their historical origins to the 14th century.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] But only in the late 17th and early 18th centuries did these terms gradually supersede *Arbëria* and *Arbëreshë* among Albanians.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] These two expressions are widely interpreted to symbolise "Children of the Eagles" and "Land of the Eagles".
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Mesolithic habitation in Albania has been evidenced in several open-air sites which were close to the Adriatic coastline and in caves.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Mesolithic objects found in a cave near Xarrë include flint and jasper objects along with fossilised animal bones, while those discoveries at Mount Dajt comprise bone and stone tools similar to those of the Aurignacian culture.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The Neolithic era in Albania began around 7000 BC and is evidenced in finds which indicate domestication of sheep and goats and small-scale agriculture.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] A part of the Neolithic population may have been the same as the Mesolithic population of the southern Balkans, like in the Konispol cave, where the Mesolithic stratum co-exists with Pre-Pottery Neolithic finds.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Cardium pottery culture appears in coastal Albania and across the Adriatic after 6500 BC, while the settlements of the interior took part in the processes that formed the Starčevo culture.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The Albanian bitumen mines of Selenicë provide early evidence of bitumen exploitation in Europe, dating to Late Neolithic Albania (from 5000 BC), when local communities used it as pigment for ceramic decoration, waterproofing, and adhesive for repairing broken vessels.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The bitumen of Selenicë circulated towards eastern Albania from the early 5th millennium BC.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] First evidence of its overseas trade export comes from the Neolithic and Bronze Age southern Italy.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The high-quality bitumen of Selenicë has been exploited throughout all the historical ages since the Late Neolithic era until today.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The Indo-Europeanisation of Albania in the context of the IE-isation of the western Balkans began after 2800 BC.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The presence of the Early Bronze Age tumuli in the vicinity of later Apollonia dates to 2679±174 calBC (2852–2505 calBC).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] These burial mounds belong to the southern expression of the Adriatic-Ljubljana culture (related to the later Cetina culture), which moved southwards along the Adriatic from the northern Balkans.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The same community built similar mounds in Montenegro (Rakića Kuće) and northern Albania (Shtoj).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The first archaeogenetic find related to the IE-isation of Albania involves a man with predominantly Yamnaya ancestry buried in a tumulus of northeastern Albania, which dates to 2663–2472 calBC.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] During the Middle Bronze Age, Cetina culture sites and finds appear in Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Cetina culture moved southwards across the Adriatic from the Cetina valley of Dalmatia.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The incorporated territory of Albania was historically inhabited by Indo-European peoples, amongst them numerous Illyrian and Epirote tribes.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The territory referred to as Illyria corresponded roughly to the area east of the Adriatic Sea in the Mediterranean Sea, extending in the south to the mouth of the Vjosë.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The first account of the Illyrian groups comes from the Periplus of the Euxine Sea, a Greek text written in the 4th century BC.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The Bryges were also present in central Albania, while the south was inhabited by the Epirote Chaonians, whose capital was at Phoenice.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Other colonies, such as Apollonia and Epidamnos, were established by Greek city-states on the coast by the 7th century BC.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The Illyrian Taulanti were a powerful Illyrian tribe among the earliest recorded tribes in the area.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] They lived in an area that corresponds with much of present-day Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Together with the Dardanian ruler Cleitus, Glaucias, the ruler of the Taulantian kingdom, fought against Alexander the Great at the Battle of Pelium in 335 BC.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] As time passed, the ruler of Ancient Macedonia, Cassander of Macedon, captured Apollonia and crossed the river Genusus (Albanian: *Shkumbin*) in 314 BC.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] A few years later, Glaucias laid siege to Apollonia and captured the Greek colony of Epidamnos.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The Illyrian Ardiaei tribe, centred in Montenegro, ruled over most of the territory of northern Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Their Ardiaean Kingdom reached its greatest extent under King Agron, the son of Pleuratus II.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Agron extended his rule over other neighbouring tribes as well.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Following Agron's death in 230 BC, his wife, Teuta, inherited the Ardiaean kingdom.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Teuta's forces extended their operations further southwards to the Ionian Sea.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] In 229 BC, Rome declared war on the kingdom for extensively plundering Roman ships.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The war ended in an Illyrian defeat in 227 BC.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Teuta was eventually succeeded by Gentius in 181 BC.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Gentius clashed with the Romans in 168 BC, initiating the Third Illyrian War.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The conflict resulted in the Roman conquest of the region by 167 BC.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The Romans split the region into three administrative divisions.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The Roman Empire was split in 395 upon the death of Theodosius I into an Eastern and Western Roman Empire, in part because of the increasing pressure from threats during the Barbarian Invasions.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] From the 6th century into the 7th century, the Slavs crossed the Danube and largely absorbed the indigenous Greeks, Illyrians, and Thracians in the Balkans; thus, the Illyrians were mentioned for the last time in historical records in the 7th century.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] In the 11th century, the Great Schism formalised the break of communion between the Eastern Orthodox and Western Catholic Church, which is reflected in Albania through the emergence of a Catholic north and Orthodox south.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The Albanian people inhabited the west of Lake Ochrida and the upper valley of the River Shkumbin and established the Principality of Arbanon in 1190 under the leadership of Progon of Kruja.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The realm was succeeded by his sons Gjin Progoni and Demetrio Progoni.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Upon the death of Dhimiter, the territory came under the rule of the Albanian-Greek Gregorios Kamonas and subsequently under the Golem of Kruja.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] In the 13th century, the principality was dissolved.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Arbanon is considered to be the first sketch of an Albanian state, which retained a semi-autonomous status as the western extremity of the Byzantine Empire, under the Byzantine Doukai of Epirus or Laskarids of Nicaea.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Towards the end of the 12th and beginning of the 13th centuries, Serbs and Venetians began to take possession of the territory.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The ethnogenesis of the Albanians is uncertain; however, the first undisputed mention of Albanians dates back in historical records from 1079 or 1080 in a work by Michael Attaleiates, who referred to the Albanoi as having taken part in a revolt against Constantinople.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] At this point, the Albanians were fully Christianised.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] After the dissolution of Arbanon, Charles I of Anjou concluded an agreement with the Albanian rulers, promising to protect them and their ancient liberties.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] In 1272, he established the Kingdom of Albania and conquered regions back from the Despotate of Epirus.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The kingdom claimed all of central Albania territory from Dyrrhachium along the Adriatic Sea coast down to Butrint.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] A Catholic political structure was a basis for the papal plans of spreading Catholicism in the Balkan Peninsula.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] This plan also found the support of Helen of Anjou.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Around 30 Catholic churches and monasteries were built during her rule, mainly in northern Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Internal power struggles within the Byzantine Empire in the 14th century enabled Serbs' most powerful medieval ruler, Stefan Dušan, to establish a short-lived empire that included all of Albania except Durrës.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] In 1367, Albanian rulers established the Despotate of Arta.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] During that time, several Albanian principalities were established, notably the Principality of Albania, the Principality of Kastrioti, the Lordship of Berat, and the Principality of Dukagjini.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] In the first half of the 15th century, the Ottoman Empire invaded most of Albania, and the League of Lezhë was organized under Skanderbeg as a ruler, who became the national hero of the Albanian medieval history.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] that halted Ottoman advance into Europe for 25 years.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] With the fall of Constantinople, the Ottoman Empire entered an extended period of military conquest and expansion, with its borders gradually expanding deep into Southeast Europe.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] In 1385, they reached the Albanian Ionian Sea Coast, while in 1415, they established their garrisons across Southern Albania, eventually occupying most of Albania in 1431.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Thousands of Albanians consequently fled to Western Europe, particularly to Calabria, Naples, Ragusa, and Sicily, while numerous others sought protection at the often inaccessible Mountains of Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Since the vast majority of Albanians were adherents of Christianity, they were considered an inferior class of people, resulting in them being discriminated against in various forms, including being subjected to heavy taxes.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Additionally, the Devshirme system allowed the Sultan to collect a requisite percentage of Christian adolescents from their families to compose the Janissary.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The Ottoman conquest was also accompanied by the gradual process of Islamisation and the rapid construction of mosques.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] A prosperous and longstanding revolution erupted after the formation of the League of Lezhë until the fall of Shkodër under the leadership of Gjergj Kastrioti Skanderbeg, who consistently defeated major Ottoman armies led by Sultans Murad II and Mehmed II.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Skanderbeg managed to unite several of the Albanian principalities, amongst them the Arianitis, Dukagjinis, Zaharias, and Thopias, and establish a centralised authority over most of the non-conquered territories, becoming the Lord of Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Despite his competence as a military leader, Skanderbeg's victories over the Ottoman Empire's military had only a short-term impact, as his forces were unable to halt the Ottomans' advancement permanently; therefore, they successfully delayed the final conquest of Albanian lands only temporarily.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The constant Ottoman invasions caused enormous destruction to Albania, greatly reducing the population and destroying flocks of livestock and crops.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Besides surrender, there was no possible way Skanderbeg would be able to halt the Ottoman invasions despite his military forces achieving several consecutive victories against them.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Among other factors, his manpower and resources were insufficient for a prolonged war, preventing him from expanding the war efforts and driving the Turks from the Albanian borders.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Albania was therefore doomed to face an unending series of Ottoman attacks until it eventually fell years after his death.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] When the Ottomans were gaining a firm foothold in the region, Albanian towns were organised into four principal sanjaks.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The government fostered trade by settling a sizeable Jewish colony of refugees fleeing persecution in Spain.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The city of Vlorë saw passing through its ports imported merchandise from Europe, such as velvets, cotton goods, mohairs, carpets, spices, and leather from Bursa and Constantinople.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Some citizens of Vlorë even had business associates throughout Europe.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The phenomenon of Islamisation among the Albanians became primarily widespread from the 17th century and continued into the 18th century.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Islam offered them equal opportunities and advancement within the Ottoman Empire.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] However, according to some scholars, motives for conversion were diverse depending on the context; although the lack of source material significantly hampers efforts to investigate such issues.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] As a result of the Ottomans' increasing suppression of Catholicism, most Catholic Albanians converted in the 17th century, while Orthodox Albanians followed suit mainly in the following century.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Since the Albanian-inhabited regions were considered strategically important, Albanians made up a significant proportion of the Ottoman Empire's military and bureaucracy.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Consequently, many Muslim Albanians attained important political and military positions, while their work made a significant cultural contribution to the broader Muslim world.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Enjoying this privileged position, they held various high administrative positions, which, among others, included over two dozen Albanians serving as Grand viziers of the Ottoman Empire.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Additionally, other distinguished Albanians included members of the prominent Köprülü family, Zagan Pasha, Muhammad Ali of Egypt, and Ali Pasha of Tepelena.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Furthermore, two Ottoman sultans, Bayezid II and Mehmed III, were born to mothers of Albanian ethnic backgrounds.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The Albanian Renaissance was a period with its roots in the late 18th century and continuing into the 19th century, during which the Albanian people gathered spiritual and intellectual strength for an independent cultural and political life within an independent nation.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Modern Albanian culture flourished too, especially Albanian literature and arts, and was frequently linked to the influences of the Romanticism and Enlightenment principles.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Prior to the rise of nationalism, Ottoman authorities suppressed any expression of national unity or conscience by the Albanian people.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The victory of Russia over the Ottoman Empire following the Russian-Ottoman Wars resulted the execution of the Treaty of San Stefano which assigned Albanian-populated lands to their Slavic and Greek neighbours.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] However, the United Kingdom and Austro-Hungarian Empire consequently blocked the arrangement and caused the Treaty of Berlin.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] From this point, Albanians started to organise themselves with the goal to protect and unite the Albanian-populated lands into a unitary nation, leading to the formation of the League of Prizren.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The league had initially the assistance of the Ottoman authorities whose position was based on the religious solidarity of Muslim people and landlords connected with the Ottoman administration.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] They favoured and protected the Muslim solidarity and called for defence of Muslim lands simultaneously constituting the reason for titling the league Committee of the Real Muslims.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Approximately 300 Muslims participated in the assembly composed by delegates from Bosnia, the administrator of the Sanjak of Prizren as representatives of the central authorities and no delegates from Vilayet of Scutari.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Ottomans authorities cancelled their assistance when the league, under Abdyl Frashëri, became focused on working towards Albanian autonomy and requested merging four vilayets, including Kosovo, Shkodër, Monastir and Ioannina, into a unified vilayet, the Albanian Vilayet.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The league used military force to prevent the annexing areas of Plav and Gusinje assigned to Montenegro.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] After several successful battles with Montenegrin troops, such as the Battle of Novšiće, the league was forced to retreat from their contested regions.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The league was later defeated by the Ottoman army sent by the sultan.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Albania declared independence from the Ottoman Empire on 28 November 1912, accompanied by the establishment of the Senate and Government by the Assembly of Vlorë on 4 December 1912.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Its sovereignty was recognised by the Conference of London.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] On 29 July 1913, the Treaty of London delineated the borders of the country and its neighbors, leaving many Albanians outside Albania, predominantly partitioned between Montenegro, Serbia, and Greece.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Headquartered in Vlorë, the International Commission of Control was established on 15 October 1913 to take care of the administration of Albania until its own political institutions were in order.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The International Gendarmerie was established as the Principality of Albania's first law enforcement agency.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] In November, the first gendarmerie members arrived in the country.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Prince of Albania Wilhelm of Wied *(Princ Vilhelm Vidi)* was selected as the first prince of the principality.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] On 7 March, he arrived in the provisional capital of Durrës and began to organise his government, appointing Turhan Pasha Përmeti to form the first Albanian cabinet.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] In November 1913, the Albanian pro-Ottoman forces had offered the throne of Albania to the Ottoman war minister of Albanian origin, Ahmed Izzet Pasha.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The pro-Ottoman peasants believed that the new regime was a tool of the six Christian Great Powers and local landowners, who owned half of the arable land.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] In February 1914, the Autonomous Republic of Northern Epirus was proclaimed in Gjirokastër by the local Greek population against incorporation to Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] This initiative was short-lived, and in 1921 the southern provinces were incorporated into the Albanian Principality.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] High-ranking Orthodox clergy were among the strongest opponents of the Albanian National Awakening.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Reports from the period, including those from international observers, documented the burning of villages and civilian casualties.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Nationalist Orthodox insurgents were accused of targeting Muslim Albanian populations to consolidate territorial claims for Greece.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Meanwhile, the revolt of Albanian peasants against the new regime erupted under the leadership of the group of Muslim clerics gathered around Essad Pasha Toptani, who proclaimed himself the savior of Albania and Islam.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] To gain the support of the Mirdita Catholic volunteers from northern Albania, Prince Wied appointed their leader, Prênk Bibë Doda, foreign minister of the Principality of Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] In May and June 1914, the International Gendarmerie was joined by Isa Boletini and his men, mostly from Kosovo, and the rebels defeated northern Mirdita Catholics, capturing most of Central Albania by the end of August 1914.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Prince Wied's regime collapsed, and he left the country on 3 September 1914.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The interwar period in Albania was marked by persistent economic and social difficulties, political instability and foreign interventions.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] After World War I, Albania lacked an established government and internationally recognised borders, rendering it vulnerable to neighboring entities such as Greece, Italy, and Yugoslavia, all of which sought to expand their influence.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] This led to political uncertainty, highlighted in 1918 when the Congress of Durrës sought Paris Peace Conference protection but was denied, further complicating Albania's position on the international stage.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Territorial tensions escalated as Yugoslavia, particularly Serbia, sought control of northern Albania, while Greece aimed dominance in southern Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The situation deteriorated in 1919 when the Serbs launched attacks on Albanian inhabitants, among others in Gusinje and Plav, resulting in massacres and large-scale displacement.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Meanwhile, Italian influence continued to expand during this time, driven by economic interests and political ambitions.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Fan Noli, renowned for his idealism, became prime minister in 1924, with a vision to institute a Western-style constitutional government, abolish feudalism, counter Italian influence, and enhance critical sectors, including infrastructure, education and healthcare.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] He faced resistance from former allies, who had assisted in the removal of Zog from power, and struggled to secure foreign aid to implement his agenda.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Noli's decision to establish diplomatic ties with the Soviet Union, an adversary of the Serbian elite, ignited allegations of bolshevism from Belgrade.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] This in turn led to increased pressure from Italy and culminated in Zog's restoration to authority.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] In 1928, Zog transitioned Albania from a republic to a monarchy that garnered backing from Fascist Italy, with Zog assuming the title of King Zog I.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Key constitutional changes dissolved the Senate and established a unicameral National Assembly while preserving Zog's authoritative powers.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] In 1939, Italy under Benito Mussolini launched a military invasion of Albania, resulting in the exile of Zog and the creation of an Italian protectorate.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] As World War II progressed, Italy aimed to expand its territorial dominion in the Balkans, including territorial claims on regions of Greece (Chameria), Macedonia, Montenegro and Kosovo.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] These ambitions laid the foundation of Greater Albania, which aimed to unite all areas with Albanian-majority populations into a single country.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] In 1943, as Italy's control declined, Nazi Germany assumed control of Albania, subjecting Albanians to forced labour, economic exploitation and repression under German rule.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] This period saw the forced expulsion and massacres of the Cham Albanians, a predominantly Muslim group.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The religious divide was used as a justification for violence, with some Orthodox locals reportedly identifying Muslim neighbors to paramilitary groups, leading to massacres and the forced expulsion of thousands.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The tide shifted in 1944 when Albanian partisan forces, under the leadership of Enver Hoxha and other communist leaders, successfully liberated Albania from German occupation.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The establishment of the People's Republic of Albania under the leadership of Enver Hoxha was a significant epoch in modern Albanian history.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Hoxha's regime embraced Marxist–Leninist ideologies and implemented authoritarian policies, including prohibition of religious practices, severe restrictions on travel, and abolition of private property rights.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] It was also defined by a persistent pattern of purges, extensive repression, instances of betrayal, and hostility to external influences.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Any form of opposition or resistance to his rule was met with expeditious and severe consequences, such as internal exile, extended imprisonment, and execution.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The regime confronted a multitude of challenges, including widespread poverty, illiteracy, health crises and gender inequality.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] In response, Hoxha initiated a modernisation initiative aimed at attaining economic and social liberation and transforming Albania into an industrial society.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Albania's diplomatic history under Hoxha was characterised by notable conflicts.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Initially aligned with Yugoslavia as a satellite state, the relationship deteriorated as Yugoslavia aimed to incorporate Albania within its territory.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Subsequently, Albania established relations with the Soviet Union and engaged trade agreements with other Eastern European countries, but experienced disagreements over Soviet policies, leading to strained ties with Moscow and diplomatic separation in 1961.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Simultaneously, tensions with the West heightened due to Albania's refusal to hold free elections and allegations of Western support for anti-communist uprisings.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Albania's enduring partnership was with China; it sided with Beijing during the Sino-Soviet conflict, resulting in severed ties with the Soviet Union and withdrawal from the Warsaw Pact in response to the invasion of Czechoslovakia in 1968.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] But their relations stagnated in 1970, prompting both to reassess their commitment, and Albania actively reduced its dependence on China.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Under Hoxha's regime, Albania underwent a widespread campaign targeting religious clergy of various faiths, resulting in public persecution and executions, particularly targeting Muslims, Roman Catholics and Eastern Orthodox adherents.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] In 1946, religious estates underwent nationalisation, coinciding with the closure or transformation of religious institutions into various other purposes.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] This culminated in 1976, when Albania became the world's first constitutionally atheist state.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Under this regime, citizens were forced to renounce their religious beliefs, adopt a secular way of life, and embrace socialist ideology.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] After four decades of communism paired with the revolutions of 1989, Albania witnessed a notable rise in political activism, particularly among students, which led to a transformation in the prevailing order.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] After the first multi-party elections of 1991, the communist party maintained a stronghold in the parliament until its defeat in the parliamentary elections of 1992 directed by the Democratic Party.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Considerable economic and financial resources were devoted to pyramid schemes that were widely supported by the government.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The schemes swept up somewhere between one sixth and one third of the population of the country.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Despite the International Monetary Fund's warnings, Sali Berisha defended the schemes as large investment firms, leading more people to redirect their remittances and sell their homes and cattle for cash to deposit in the schemes.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The schemes began to collapse in late 1996, leading many of the investors to join initially peaceful protests against the government, requesting their money back.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The protests turned violent in February 1997 as government forces responded by firing on the demonstrators.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] In March, the Police and Republican Guard deserted, leaving their armories open.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] These were promptly emptied by militias and criminal gangs.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The resulting civil war caused a wave of evacuations of foreign nationals and refugees.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The crisis led both Aleksandër Meksi and Sali Berisha to resign from office in the wake of the general election.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] In April 1997, Operation Alba, a U.N. peacekeeping force led by Italy, entered Albania with two goals: to assist with the evacuation of expatriates and secure the ground for international organisations.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The main international organisation involved was the Western European Union's multinational Albanian Police element, which worked with the government to restructure the judicial system and simultaneously the Albanian police.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] After the fall of the communist system, Albania pursued integration with Euro-Atlantic institutions.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] It formally applied for membership of the European Union on 28 April 2009 and joined NATO the same year.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Albania was granted EU candidate status in June 2014, while accession negotiations began with the first intergovernmental conference in July 2022.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Albania opened negotiations on the fundamentals cluster in October 2024 and, by late 2025, had opened all negotiating clusters, a development described by the European Commission as a significant milestone in the accession process.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The 2013 Albanian parliamentary election ended eight years of Democratic Party rule under Sali Berisha.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The Socialist Party, led by Edi Rama, won the election as the main force of the Alliance for a European Albania, with the Socialist Movement for Integration as a coalition partner.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Rama's governments promoted judicial reform, public administration changes, urban redevelopment, digitalisation of public services, tourism development and EU accession as central priorities.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] A major justice reform package adopted in 2016 created new institutions including the Special Structure against Corruption and Organized Crime (SPAK), which later became central to the prosecution of high-level corruption and organised crime cases.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] At the same time, Rama's long tenure became increasingly controversial.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The Socialist Party won the 2017, 2021 and 2025 parliamentary elections, making Rama the first Albanian prime minister to secure four consecutive mandates.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] His dominance was accompanied by persistent criticism from opposition parties, civil society and international monitors over corruption, weak checks and balances, state capture, media pressure and the use of state resources in elections.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Freedom House has classified Albania as "Partly Free" and as a "Transitional or Hybrid Regime", while noting that elections are competitive but that politics is highly polarised, organised around dominant personalities, and affected by corruption and bribery.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Freedom House's *Nations in Transit* assessment described Albania's national governance as democratic but dominated by clientelist party politics and individual personalities, and stated that elections were frequently marred by vote-buying, manipulation, fraud and gerrymandering.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Concerns about state capture also became a recurring theme in assessments of Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] In 2021, Transparency International and the Institute for Democracy and Mediation published *Deconstructing State Capture in Albania*, a report examining grand corruption cases and "tailor-made laws" from 2008 to 2020.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The report argued that state-capture mechanisms in Albania involved clientelist networks, corruption in the judiciary and laws designed to benefit particular private interests.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Electoral integrity remained disputed during Rama's later terms.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The OSCE Office for Democratic Institutions and Human Rights stated that the 2025 Albanian parliamentary election was competitive and professionally managed, but that it took place in a highly polarised environment and contestants did not enjoy a level playing field.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The final report cited reports of intimidation, misuse of public resources and pressure on public employees, which undermined equal opportunities.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Reuters reported that the 2025 campaign was dominated by Rama's promise to secure EU membership by 2030 and by accusations of widespread corruption, while critics argued that he had concentrated too much power.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] After the election, Rama began his fourth term in September 2025 and declared EU membership by 2030 the central goal of his mandate.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The consolidation of Rama's rule coincided with a wave of investigations by SPAK against high-ranking figures from both the governing majority and the opposition.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Deputy prime minister and infrastructure minister Belinda Balluku was later investigated over public-tender allegations, denied wrongdoing, and was dismissed by Rama in February 2026 as the case intensified.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] European Union officials praised SPAK's work as central to rule-of-law reform, while also warning that Albania's EU progress depended on judicial independence and credible anti-corruption results.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] On 26 November 2019, a 6.4 magnitude earthquake struck Albania, with the epicentre about 16 km (10 mi) southwest of Mamurras.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The tremor was felt in Tirana and in places as far away as Taranto, Italy, and Belgrade, Serbia, while the most affected areas were Durrës and Kodër-Thumanë.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The response included humanitarian aid from the Albanian diaspora and several foreign governments.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] On 9 March 2020, the COVID-19 pandemic was confirmed to have spread to Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] In 2026, large anti-government demonstrations known as the Flamingo Revolution emerged after proposed luxury coastal developments on Sazan Island and the Zvërnec peninsula, including projects linked to Jared Kushner, became a focus of environmental and anti-corruption protests.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] Demonstrators accused Rama's government of lacking transparency, endangering protected ecosystems and failing to tackle corruption or improve public services.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] The protests, initially centred on environmental protection, expanded into broader demands for government accountability, early elections and Rama's resignation.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p01] European Parliament figures also warned that the coastal-development plans could affect Albania's EU accession process if they conflicted with environmental obligations and democratic standards.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Albania lies along the Mediterranean Sea on the Balkan Peninsula in South and Southeast Europe, and has an area of 28,748 km2 (11,100 sq mi).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] It is bordered by the Adriatic Sea to the west, Montenegro to the northwest, Kosovo to the northeast, North Macedonia to the east, Greece to the south, and the Ionian Sea to the southwest.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] It is between latitudes 42° and 39° N and longitudes 21° and 19° E.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Geographic coordinates include Vërmosh at 42° 35' 34" northern latitude as the northernmost point, Konispol at 39° 40' 0" northern latitude as the southernmost, Sazan at 19° 16' 50" eastern longitude as the westernmost, and Vërnik at 21° 1' 26" eastern longitude as the easternmost.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Mount Korab, rising at 2,764 m (9,068.24 ft) above the Adriatic, is the highest point, while the Mediterranean Sea, at 0 m (0.00 ft), is the lowest.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The country extends 148 km (92 mi) from east to west and around 340 km (211 mi) from north to south.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Albania has a diverse and varied landscape with mountains and hills that traverse its territory in various directions.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The country is home to extensive mountain ranges, including the Albanian Alps in the north, the Korab Mountains in the east, the Pindus Mountains in the southeast, the Ceraunian Mountains in the southwest, and the Skanderbeg Mountains in the centre.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] In the northwest is the Lake of Shkodër, Southern Europe's largest lake.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Towards the southeast emerges the Lake of Ohrid, one of the world's oldest continuously existing lakes.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Farther south, the expanse includes the Large and Small Lake of Prespa, some of the Balkans' highest lakes.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Rivers rise mostly in the east and discharge into the Adriatic and Ionian Seas.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The country's longest river, measured from mouth to source, is the Drin, which starts at the confluence of its two headwaters, the Black and White Drin.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Of particular concern is the Vjosë, one of Europe's last intact large river systems.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] In Albania forest cover is around 29.% of the total land area, equivalent to 788,900 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, up from 788,800 hectares (ha) in 1990.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Of the naturally regenerating forest 11% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity) and around 0% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] For the year 2015, 97% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership, 3% private ownership and 0% with ownership listed as other or unknown.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The climate of Albania exhibits a distinguished level of variability and diversity due to the differences in latitude, longitude and altitude.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Albania experiences a Mediterranean and Continental climate, characterised by the presence of four distinct seasons.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] According to the Köppen classification, Albania encompasses five primary climatic types, spanning from Mediterranean and subtropical in the western half to oceanic, continental and subarctic in the eastern half of the country.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The coastal regions along the Adriatic and Ionian Seas in Albania are acknowledged as the warmest areas, while the northern and eastern regions encompassing the Albanian Alps and the Korab Mountains are recognised as the coldest areas in the country.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Throughout the year, the average monthly temperatures fluctuate, ranging from −1 °C (30 °F) during the winter months to 21.8 °C (71.2 °F) in the summer months.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Notably, the highest recorded temperature of 43.9 °C (111.0 °F) was observed in Kuçovë on 18 July 1973, while the lowest temperature of −29 °C (−20 °F) was recorded in Shtyllë, Librazhd on 9 January 2017.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Albania receives most of the precipitation in winter months and less in summer months.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The average precipitation is about 1,485 millimetres (58.5 inches).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The mean annual precipitation ranges between 600 and 3,000 millimetres (24 and 118 inches) depending on geographical location.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The northwestern and southeastern highlands receive the intenser amount of precipitation, whilst the northeastern and southwestern highlands as well as the Western Lowlands the more limited amount.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The Albanian Alps in the far north of the country are considered to be among the most humid regions of Europe, receiving at least 3,100 mm (122.0 in) of rain annually.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Four glaciers within these mountains were discovered at a relatively low altitude of 2,000 metres (6,600 ft), which is extremely rare for such a southerly latitude.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] A biodiversity hotspot, Albania possesses an exceptionally rich and contrasting biodiversity on account of its geographical location at the centre of the Mediterranean Sea and the great diversity in its climatic, geological and hydrological conditions.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The estuaries, wetlands and lakes are extraordinarily important for the greater flamingo, pygmy cormorant and the extremely rare and perhaps the most iconic bird of the country, the dalmatian pelican.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Of particular importance are the Mediterranean monk seal, loggerhead sea turtle and green sea turtle that use to nest on the country's coastal waters and shores.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] In terms of phytogeography, Albania is part of the Boreal Kingdom and stretches specifically within the Illyrian province of the Circumboreal and Mediterranean Region.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Its territory can be subdivided into four terrestrial ecoregions of the Palearctic realm namely within the Illyrian deciduous forests, Balkan mixed forests, Pindus Mountains mixed forests and Dinaric Mountains mixed forests.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Approximately 3,500 different species of plants can be found in Albania which refers principally to a Mediterranean and Eurasian character.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The country maintains a vibrant tradition of herbal and medicinal practices.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] At the minimum 300 plants growing locally are used in the preparation of herbs and medicines.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The trees within the forests are primarily fir, oak, beech and pine.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Albania has been an active participant in numerous international agreements and conventions aimed at strengthing its commitment to the preservation and sustainable management of biological diversity.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Since 1994, the country is a party to the Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) and its associated Cartagena and Nagoya Protocols.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] To uphold these commitments, it has developed and implemented a comprehensive National Biodiversity Strategy and Action Plan (NBSAP).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Furthermore, Albania has established a partnership with the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN), advancing its conservation efforts on both national and international scales.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Guided by the IUCN, the country has made substantial progress in the foundation of protected areas within its boundaries, encompassing 12 national parks among others Butrint, Karaburun-Sazan, Llogara, Prespa and Vjosa.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] As a signatory to the Ramsar Convention, Albania has granted special recognition upon four wetlands, designating them as Wetlands of International Importance, including Buna-Shkodër, Butrint, Karavasta and Prespa.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The country's dedication to protection extends further into the sphere of UNESCO's World Network of Biosphere Reserves, operating within the framework of the Man and the Biosphere Programme, evidenced by its engagement in the Ohrid-Prespa Transboundary Biosphere Reserve.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Furthermore, Albania is host to two natural World Heritage Sites, which encompass the Ohrid region and both the Gashi River and Rrajca as part of Ancient and Primeval Beech Forests of the Carpathians and Other Regions of Europe.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The protected areas of Albania are areas designated and managed by the Albanian government.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] There are 12 national parks, 4 ramsar sites, 1 biosphere reserve and 786 other types of conservation reserves in Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Located in the north, the Albanian Alps National Park, comprising the former Theth National Park and Valbonë Valley National Park, is surrounded amidst the towering peaks of the Albanian Alps.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] In the east, portions of the rugged Korab, Nemërçka and Shebenik Mountains are conserved within the boundaries of Fir of Hotovë-Dangëlli National Park, Shebenik National Park and Prespa National Park, with the latter encompassing Albania's share of the Great and Small Lakes of Prespa.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] To the south, the Ceraunian Mountains define the Albanian Ionian Sea Coast, shaping the landscape of Llogara National Park, which extends into the Karaburun Peninsula, forming the Karaburun-Sazan Marine Park.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Further southward lies Butrint National Park, occupying a peninsula surrounded by the Lake of Butrint and the Channel of Vivari.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] In the west, stretching along the Albanian Adriatic Sea Coast, the Divjakë-Karavasta National Park boasts the extensive Lagoon of Karavasta, one of the largest lagoon systems in the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Notably, Europe's first wild river national park, Vjosa National Park, safeguards the Vjosa River and its primary tributaries, which originates in the Pindus Mountains and flows to the Adriatic Sea.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Dajti Mountain National Park, Lurë-Dejë Mountain National Park and Tomorr Mountain National Park protect the mountainous terrain of the centre of Albania, including the Tomorr and Skanderbeg Mountains.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Environmental issues in Albania notably encompass air and water pollution, climate change impacts, waste management shortcomings, biodiversity loss and imperative for nature conservation.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Climate change is predicted to exert significant impacts on the quality of life in Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Albania is one of the European countries most at risk and vulnerable to natural disasters.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Natural disasters, such as floods, forest fires, and landslides, are increasing in Albania due to climate change, causing significant damage.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Rising sea levels are anticipated to negatively impact coastal communities and the tourism industry.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] In 2023 Albania emitted 7.67 million tonnes of greenhouse gases, equivalent to 2.73 tonnes per person, making it a relatively low emitting country.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Albania has pledged a 20.9% reduction in GHG emissions by 2030, and net zero by 2050.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The country has a moderate and improving performance in the Environmental Performance Index with an overall ranking of 62 out of 180 countries in 2022.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] However, Albania's ranking has decreased since its highest placement at position 15 in the Environmental Performance Index of 2012.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Since declaring independence in 1912, Albania has undergone several major constitutional transformations, including a monarchy, a communist one-party state, and, following the collapse of communism, the establishment of a democratic parliamentary republic.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The current constitutional order was established with the adoption of the Constitution of Albania in 1998, creating a parliamentary constitutional republic based on the separation of powers between the legislature, executive and judiciary.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Executive authority is exercised by the Prime Minister and the Council of Ministers, while the President of Albania serves as head of state with largely ceremonial and constitutional responsibilities.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Legislative authority is vested in the unicameral Parliament of Albania, elected every four years through proportional representation.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Judicial authority is exercised by an independent judiciary headed by the Constitutional Court and the Supreme Court.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Since Edi Rama and the Socialist Party of Albania came to power in 2013, Albania has experienced an unprecedented concentration of executive power, with the Socialist Party winning four consecutive parliamentary elections in 2013, 2017, 2021 and 2025.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Supporters credit Rama's governments with accelerating European Union accession negotiations, implementing the 2016 justice reform, expanding digital public services, improving infrastructure and increasing tourism.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] At the same time, Rama's prolonged tenure has generated sustained domestic and international criticism.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Opposition parties, civil society organisations and a number of analysts have argued that Albania has experienced significant democratic backsliding characterised by increasing executive dominance, weakened institutional checks and balances, clientelist governance and extensive political patronage.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Freedom House describes Albania as a "Partly Free" country and notes that politics is dominated by powerful party leaders, while corruption remains a persistent challenge.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Its *Nations in Transit* report characterises Albania's national governance as being dominated by clientelist party politics and states that elections continue to be affected by vote-buying, manipulation, fraud and gerrymandering.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Concerns regarding state capture have also featured prominently in assessments of Albania's political system.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Electoral integrity has remained a contentious issue.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Following the 2025 Albanian parliamentary election, the OSCE Office for Democratic Institutions and Human Rights concluded that the election was competitive and professionally managed, but found that it was held in a highly polarised environment without a level playing field.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The observation mission reported misuse of public resources, pressure on public employees, intimidation allegations and unequal campaign conditions that undermined equal opportunities among contestants.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The European Commission has generally praised SPAK's work while continuing to stress that corruption remains prevalent in many sectors and that judicial independence must be protected from political pressure.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] During Rama's fourth term, anti-government demonstrations intensified.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Beginning in late 2025 and expanding further during the Flamingo Revolution in 2026, protesters accused the government of systemic corruption, lack of transparency, misuse of public resources and favouring politically connected business interests.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The protests, initially triggered by opposition to coastal development projects, evolved into broader demands for democratic reform, government accountability and Rama's resignation.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Human rights protections are guaranteed by the Constitution regardless of ethnicity, language, race or religion.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Nevertheless, international organisations continue to identify concerns regarding judicial independence, corruption, media pluralism and political influence over state institutions, while noting that progress in these areas remains closely linked to Albania's European Union accession process.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Emerging from decades of isolation following the fall of communism, Albania has adopted a foreign policy orientation centred on active cooperation and engagement in international affairs.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The external affairs of Albania underscore the country's dedication to regional stability and integration into major international institutions.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Albania became a member of the United Nations (UN) in 1955, shortly after emerging from a period of isolation during the communist era.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The country reached a major achievement in its foreign policy by securing NATO membership in 2009.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Since obtaining candidate status in 2014, the country has also embarked on a comprehensive reform agenda to align itself with European Union (EU) accession standards, with the objective of becoming an EU member state.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Albania and Kosovo maintain a fraternal relationship strengthened by their substantial cultural, ethnical and historical ties.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Both countries foster enduring diplomatic ties, with Albania actively supporting Kosovo's development and international integration efforts.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Its fundamental contribution to Kosovo's path to independence is underscored by its early recognition of Kosovo's sovereignty in 2008.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Furthermore, both governments hold annual joint meetings, displayed by the inaugural meeting in 2014, which serves as an official platform to enhance bilateral cooperation and reinforce their joint commitment to policies that promote the stability and prosperity of the broader Albanian region.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The Albanian Armed Forces consist of Land, Air and Naval Forces and constitute the military and paramilitary forces of the country.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] They are led by a commander-in-chief under the supervision of the Ministry of Defence and by the President as the supreme commander during wartime.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] However, in times of peace its powers are executed through the Prime Minister and the Defence Minister.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The chief purpose of the armed forces of Albania is the defence of the independence, the sovereignty and the territorial integrity of the country, as well as the participation in humanitarian, combat, non-combat and peace support operations.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Military service is voluntary since 2010 with the age of 19 being the legal minimum age for the duty.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Albania has committed to increase the participations in multinational operations.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Since the fall of communism, the country has participated in six international missions but only one United Nations mission in Georgia, where it sent three military observers.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Since February 2008, Albania has participated officially in NATO's Operation Active Endeavor in the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] It was invited to join NATO on 3 April 2008, and it became a full member on 2 April 2009.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Albania reduced the number of active troops from 65,000 in 1988 to 14,500 in 2009.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The military now consists mainly of a small fleet of aircraft and sea vessels.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Increasing the military budget was one of the most important conditions for NATO integration.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] As of 1996 military spending was an estimated 1.5% of the country's GDP, only to peak in 2009 at 2% and fall again to 1.5%.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Human rights in Albania are formally protected by the Constitution of Albania, which guarantees equality before the law, freedom of expression, freedom of assembly, religious freedom and protection from discrimination.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] International assessments generally describe Albania as a competitive but weakened democracy, with persistent problems involving corruption, political pressure on institutions, media freedom, gender-based violence, prison conditions and discrimination against vulnerable groups.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] During the long premiership of Edi Rama, whose Socialist Party of Albania has governed since 2013, human-rights concerns have often been linked to broader criticism of democratic backsliding, concentration of executive power, clientelist party politics and weak institutional checks.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Freedom House classifies Albania as "Partly Free" and states that corruption and bribery remain major problems, while its *Nations in Transit* assessment describes national governance as dominated by clientelist party politics and individual personalities.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Opposition parties and critics have characterised Rama's rule as increasingly authoritarian, while the government and its supporters point to judicial reform, European Union accession progress and the work of anti-corruption institutions as evidence of democratic consolidation.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Freedom of expression and media independence remain major concerns.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The United States Department of State's 2024 human-rights report identified serious restrictions on freedom of expression and media freedom, including journalist self-censorship, threats and smear campaigns against journalists reporting on alleged corruption.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Reporters Without Borders has stated that journalists in Albania face political pressure, especially during elections, as well as pressure from media owners and economic insecurity.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] In the 2026 World Press Freedom Index, Albania ranked 83rd of 180 countries, with media-rights groups noting continued structural problems affecting editorial independence and journalist safety.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Freedom of assembly is generally recognised, but protest policing has drawn attention during periods of political unrest.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Authorities said the police response followed attacks on officers and damage to property, while protesters and opposition figures accused the government of using force to suppress dissent.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Corruption also has direct implications for human rights and public trust in institutions.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] International reports have repeatedly identified corruption in government, law enforcement, the judiciary and local administration as a major problem.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] In 2021, Transparency International and the Institute for Democracy and Mediation argued that Albania showed signs of state capture through grand corruption, clientelist networks and tailor-made laws benefiting private interests.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Conditions in prisons and detention facilities have remained a human-rights concern.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Amnesty International reported that people in prisons experienced overcrowding and inadequate healthcare, while the Council of Europe and Albanian authorities have identified prison reform and protection of prisoners' rights as continuing priorities.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Civil-society submissions to the UN Committee against Torture have also raised concerns about overcrowding, poor detention conditions, limited access to legal representation and insufficient investigation of abuse allegations.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Violence against women and girls remains widespread.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Nearly 60% of women in rural areas suffer physical or psychological violence and nearly 8% are victims of sexual violence.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] In 2014 the Albanian Helsinki Committee (AHC) reported that the number of female murder victims remained high.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The Commissioner for Protection from Discrimination has raised concerns regarding the family registration law that discriminates against women.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] As a result, heads of households, who are overwhelmingly men, have the right to change family residency without their partners' permission.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] In 2024, the Council of Europe's GREVIO monitoring body reported progress in Albania's framework against violence against women, but said serious gaps remained, including persistent gender stereotypes, extremely low reporting of sexual violence and limited specialist services.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] In 2026, the United Nations in Albania welcomed the adoption of a new law on prevention and protection from violence against women and domestic violence.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Roma, Balkan Egyptian and other minority communities continue to face barriers in education, housing, employment and access to public services.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] In 2024, the UN Committee on the Elimination of Racial Discrimination reviewed Albania's implementation of anti-discrimination obligations and discussed the situation of Roma and Egyptian communities, including education, legal aid and hate-speech monitoring.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Albania has legal protections against discrimination based on sexual orientation and gender identity, and LGBT organisations hold public events such as Tirana Pride.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] In 2015, ILGA-Europe ranked Albania 19th in terms of LGBT rights out of 49 observed European countries.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] In the 2022 Rainbow Europe report, lack of progress caused Albania to be ranked 28th among 49 countries.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] ILGA-Europe's later country reporting continued to identify discrimination and unsafe school environments for LGBTI people, with a 2024–2025 nationwide survey by Aleanca LGBTI reporting that most respondents viewed schools as unsafe for marginalised groups, including LGBTI students.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] are the first-level administrative units in Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Albania is defined within a territorial area of 28,748 km2 (11,100 sq mi) in the Balkan Peninsula.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] It is informally divided into three regions, the Northern, Central and Southern Regions.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Since its Declaration of Independence in 1912, Albania has reformed its internal organisation 21 times.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Presently, the primary administrative units are the twelve constituent counties (*qarqe/qarqet*), which hold equal status under the law.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] Counties had previously been used in the 1950s and were recreated on 31 July 2000 to unify the 36 districts (*rrathë/rrathët*) of that time.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The largest county in Albania by population is Tirana County with over 800,000 people.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The smallest county, by population, is Gjirokastër County with over 70,000 people.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The largest county, by area, is Korçë County encompassing 3,711 square kilometres (1,433 sq mi) of the southeast of Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The smallest county, by area, is Durrës County with an area of 766 square kilometres (296 sq mi) in the west of Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The counties are made up of 61 second-level divisions known as municipalities (*bashki/bashkia*).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] The municipalities are the first level of local governance, responsible for local needs and law enforcement.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] They unified and simplified the previous system of urban and rural municipalities or communes (*komuna/komunat*) in 2015.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] For smaller issues of local government, the municipalities are organised into 373 administrative units (*njësia*/*njësitë administrative*).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p02] There are also 2980 villages (*fshatra/fshatrat*), neighborhoods or wards (*lagje/lagjet*), and localities (*lokalitete/lokalitetet*) previously used as administrative units.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Transitioning from a socialist planned to a capitalist mixed economy, Albania is classified as a developing open market with an upper-middle income status.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The Albanian economy is characterised by a substantial service sector, comprising 48.6% of GDP, with key contributions from wholesale and retail trade, tourism, real estate, and logistics.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Following this, the industrial sector accounts for 20.2%, particularly influenced by construction, while the agricultural sector, including forestry, and fisheries, represents 18.5%, and the manufacturing sector contributes a modest 6.3% to the economy.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] As of 2025, Albania's nominal gross domestic product (GDP) is reported at $26.911 billion with a GDP per capita of $9,474.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The projected annual percentage change in economic growth for 2025 is 3.8%, with a forecasted moderation to 3.5% by 2029.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Albania has developed a comprehensive framework for international trade through several pivotal agreements with various regions.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The Stabilisation and Association Agreement (SAA) with the European Union (EU), signed in 2006, is one of the most significant.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] This agreement provides critical trade benefits and serves as a foundation for the Albanian integration into the EU.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] In 2009, Albania signed a free trade agreement (FTA) with the European Free Trade Association (EFTA), which further expands trade opportunities and market access.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The country is also a signatory to the Central European Free Trade Agreement (CEFTA) and Organization of the Black Sea Economic Cooperation (BSEC), promoting regional trade and collaboration with neighboring countries.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Furthermore, the country has enhanced its bilateral trade relations through a FTA with Turkey, the United Kingdom and a bilateral investment treaty with the United States.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The 2023 Economic Freedom of the World report placed Albania in the 31st position, noting a considerable degree of economic independence and the effective adoption of market-oriented policies.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The 2024 Bertelsmann Transformation Index ranked Albania 20th and acknowledged substantial progress in political and economic transformation.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Also in 2024, the country was positioned 23rd in the Global Gender Gap Index, excelling in the Economic Participation and Opportunity category with a global ranking of 16th, showcasing significant advancements in women's economic participation.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] However, the Albanian economy, despite demonstrating considerable resilience, encounters substantial vulnerabilities that hinder its development.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Principal challenges include widespread corruption, distorted competition, and frequent modifications to fiscal legislation.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Furthermore, inadequate contract enforcement, a large informal sector, and persistent labor shortages further complicate the national economic progress.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Economic landscape of Albania is characterised by regional disparities, particularly apparent in the concentration of economic activities in the triangular region formed by Tirana, Durrës and Laç.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] This metropolitan area, referred to as Durana, functions as the principal economic center of Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] In the year 2021, Tirana County accounted for a significant 44% of the national GDP, with the counties of Fier and Durrës also playing integral roles in the economy, contributing 11% and 10% to the GDP, respectively.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Other substantial economic centers, such as Elbasan and the coastal cities of Sarandë and Vlorë, highlight the uneven distribution of economic development across the country.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Cultural regions, including Berat and Korçë, despite their geographical distance from the primary economic hubs, have derived considerable benefits from the expansion of the tourism sector.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Concerns over illicit finance, money laundering and organised-crime influence have become increasingly prominent in assessments of Albania's economy.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The United States Department of State has identified Albania as vulnerable to money laundering, with criminal proceeds laundered through real estate purchases, construction projects, virtual assets and business development.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Its 2025 Investment Climate Statement also described Albania's economic development as vulnerable because of widespread corruption, organised crime, distorted competition, labour shortages, low productivity and a large informal sector.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The Global Initiative Against Transnational Organized Crime's 2025 Global Organized Crime Index described Albania as a prominent destination for money laundering, stating that criminal organisations exploit the real estate, tourism and construction sectors to legitimise illicit profits.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] It also reported that the construction sector is heavily infiltrated by illicit funds, distorting the market, and that corruption within political and law-enforcement institutions continues to facilitate organised crime.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The government has generally rejected accusations of political protection for organised crime and has pointed to justice reform, anti-money-laundering measures and investigations by the Special Structure against Corruption and Organized Crime as evidence of progress.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Further, the country is a worldwide significant producer of salvia, rosemary and yellow gentian.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The country's proximity to the Ionian Sea and the Adriatic Sea give the underdeveloped fishing industry great potential.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The World Bank and European Community economists report that, Albania's fishing industry has good potential to generate export earnings because prices in the nearby Greek and Italian markets are many times higher than those in the Albanian market.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The fish available off the coasts of the country are carp, trout, sea bream, mussels and crustaceans.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Albania has one of Europe's longest histories of viticulture.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Today's region was one of the few places where vine was naturally grown during the ice age.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The oldest found seeds in the region are 4,000 to 6,000 years old.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] In 2009, the nation produced an estimated 17,500 tonnes of wine.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Albania's secondary sector has undergone many changes and diversification since the communist regime collapsed.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] It is very diversified, from electronics, manufacturing, textiles, to food, cement, mining, and energy.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The Antea Cement plant in Fushë-Krujë is considered one of the nation's largest industrial greenfield investments.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Albanian oil and gas is one of the most promising, albeit strictly regulated, sectors of its economy.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Albania has the second-largest oil deposits in the Balkan peninsula after Romania, and the largest oil reserves in Europe.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The Albpetrol company is owned by the Albanian state and monitors the state petroleum agreements in the country.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The textile industry has seen an extensive expansion by approaching companies from the European Union (EU) in Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] According to the Instituti i Statistikës (INSTAT), as of 2016, textile production had an annual growth of 5.3% and an annual turnover of around 1.5 billion euros.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Albania is a significant minerals producer and ranks among the world's leading chromium producers and exporters.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The nation is also a notable producer of copper, nickel, and coal.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The Batra mine, Bulqizë mine, and Thekna mine are among the most recognised Albanian mines still in operation.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The tertiary sector represents the fastest growing sector of the country's economy.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] 36% of the population work in the service sector which contributes to 65% of the country's GDP.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Ever since the end of the 20th century, the banking industry is a major component of the tertiary sector and remains in good conditions overall due to privatisation and the commendable monetary policy.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Previously one of the most isolated and controlled countries in the world, telecommunication industry represents nowadays another major contributor to the sector.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] It developed largely through privatisation and subsequent investment by both domestic and foreign investors.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Eagle, Vodafone and Telekom Albania are the leading telecommunications service providers in the country.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Tourism is recognised as an industry of national importance and has been steadily increasing since the beginnings of the 21st century.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] It directly accounted for 8.4% of GDP in 2016 though including indirect contributions pushes the proportion to 26%.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] In the same year, the country received approximately 4.74 million visitors mostly from across Europe and the United States as well.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The increase of foreign visitors has been dramatic.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Albania had only 500,000 visitors in 2005, and an estimated 4.2 million in 2012, an increase of 740 percent.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] According to the United Nations World Tourism Organization (UN Tourism), Albania welcomed approximately 11.7 million tourists in 2024, marking a significant increase from previous years.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The bulk of the tourist industry is concentrated along the Adriatic and Ionian Sea in the west of the country.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] But the Albanian Riviera in the southwest has the most scenic and pristine beaches; its coastline has a considerable length of 446 kilometres (277 miles).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The coast has a distinctive character, rich in varieties of virgin beaches, capes, coves, covered bays, lagoons, small gravel beaches, sea caves, and many landforms.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Some parts of this seaside are very clean ecologically, including unexplored areas, which are very rare within the Mediterranean.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Other attractions include the mountainous areas such as the Albanian Alps, Ceraunian Mountains and Korab Mountains but also the historical cities of Berat, Durrës, Gjirokastër, Sarandë, Shkodër and Korçë.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The international airport of Tirana is the premier air gateway to the country, and is also the principal hub for Albania's national flag carrier airline, Air Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The airport carried more than 3.3 million passengers in 2019 with connections to many destinations in other countries around Europe, Africa and Asia.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The country plans to progressively increase the number of airports especially in the south with possible locations in Sarandë, Gjirokastër and Vlorë.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The highways and motorways in Albania are properly maintained and often still under construction and renovation.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The Autostrada 1 (A1) is an integral transportation corridor and the country's longest motorway.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] It is planned to link Durrës on the Adriatic Sea across Pristina in Kosovo with the Pan-European Corridor X in Serbia.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The Autostrada 2 (A2) is part of the Adriatic–Ionian Corridor as well as the Pan-European Corridor VIII and connects Fier with Vlorë.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The Autostrada 3 (A3) is under construction and after its completion will connect Tirana and Elbasan with the Pan-European Corridor VIII.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] When all three corridors are completed, Albania will have an estimated 759 kilometres (472 mi) of highway, linking it with all neighboring countries.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Durrës is the busiest and largest seaport in the country, followed by Vlorë, Shëngjin and Sarandë.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The rail network is administered by the national railway company Hekurudha Shqiptare.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] A new railway line from Tirana and its airport to Durrës is planned.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The location of this railway, connecting Albania's most populated urban areas, makes it an important economic development project.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Due to its location and natural resources, Albania has a wide variety of energy resources, ranging from gas, oil, and coal to wind, solar, water, and other renewable sources.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] According to the World Economic Forum's 2023 Energy Transition Index (ETI), the country ranked 21st globally, highlighting the progress in its energy transition agenda.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Currently, Albania's electricity generation sector depends on hydroelectricity, ranking fifth in the world in percentage terms.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Increasing risks of river floods and droughts due to climate change is expected to put electricity generation at risk.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The Drin, in the north, hosts four hydroelectric power stations, including Fierza, Koman, Skavica and Vau i Dejës.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Two other power stations, such as the Banjë and Moglicë, are along the Devoll in the south.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] It has the 10th-largest oil reserves in Europe and the 58th in the world.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The country's main petroleum deposits are located around the Albanian Adriatic Sea Coast and Myzeqe Plain within the Western Lowlands, where the country's largest reserve is located.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Patos-Marinza, also located within the area, is the largest onshore oil field in Europe.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The Trans Adriatic Pipeline (TAP), part of the planned Southern Gas Corridor, runs for 215 kilometres (134 miles) across Albania's territory before entering the Albanian Adriatic Sea Coast approximately 17 kilometres (11 miles) northwest of Fier.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Albania's water resources are particularly abundant in all the regions of the country and comprise lakes, rivers, springs, and groundwater aquifers.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The country's available average quantity of fresh water is estimated at 129.7 cubic metres (4,580 cubic feet) per inhabitant per year, one of the highest rates in Europe.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] According to data presented by the Joint Monitoring Programme for Water Supply and Sanitation (JMP) in 2015, about 93% of the country's total population had access to improved sanitation.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The freedom of press and freedom of speech, and the right to free expression are guaranteed by the Constitution of Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] In practice, however, media freedom has been weakened by political pressure, concentrated ownership, opaque financing, intimidation of journalists and the overlap between media, business and political interests.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Albania ranked 84th in the World Press Freedom Index of 2020 compiled by Reporters Without Borders.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Reporters Without Borders has continued to describe the Albanian media environment as fragile, stating that press freedom and media independence are threatened by conflicts of interest between business and politics, a flawed legal framework and partisan regulation.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] In 2026, Albania ranked 83rd of 180 countries in the World Press Freedom Index.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Radio Televizioni Shqiptar (RTSH) is the public broadcaster of Albania, operating television and radio stations throughout the country.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The main private broadcasters include Top Channel, TV Klan, Vizion Plus, A2 CNN, Syri TV and Ora News.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Albanian television content is also distributed in Kosovo and other Albanian-speaking territories.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Reporters Without Borders states that the most influential private-sector media are owned by a small number of companies with links to the political world and to highly regulated sectors such as construction.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The Media Freedom Rapid Response reported that the top four owners in the Albanian television market reach between 48.93% and 58.60% of audiences, and that the boundaries between media, politics and economics remain blurred.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] According to these assessments, media owners often use their outlets to protect business interests or influence governments and political parties, while state advertising and public funds are distributed in opaque ways that can create political dependence.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The media environment has become a central part of criticism of Prime Minister Edi Rama's long rule.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] International media-freedom organisations and Albanian journalists have accused the government of using communication centralisation, selective access, public-relations material and attacks on critical reporters to dominate the information space.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Reporters Without Borders has stated that journalists face political pressure, especially during elections, and that politicians limit editorial independence by politicising regulators and the public broadcaster.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The Media Freedom Rapid Response cited BIRN Albania editor Gjergj Erebara as saying that large parts of the Albanian media landscape operate under government propaganda and disinformation pressure.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Journalists who investigate corruption, organised crime or politically connected business interests face particular risks.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Reporters Without Borders states that journalists investigating crime and corruption are frequent targets of threats and that self-censorship is widespread.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] It also reports that critical journalists are subjected to discrediting attacks by both government and opposition politicians, while organised crime remains a major threat to journalists' safety.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] In March 2023, the headquarters of Top Channel was attacked with automatic weapons, killing a security guard.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The public broadcaster has also been part of the debate over media capture and political pressure.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] In 2026, international media-freedom organisations warned that democratic reform of RTSH should not be carried out through funding cuts, suspension or closure, arguing that such measures would violate European standards for public service media.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Albanian cinema has its roots in the 20th century and developed after the country's declaration of independence.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The first movie theater exclusively devoted to showing motion pictures was built in 1912 in Shkodër.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] During the People's Republic of Albania, Albanian cinema developed rapidly with the inauguration of the Kinostudio Shqipëria e Re in Tirana.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] In 1953, the Albanian-Soviet epic film *The Great Warrior Skanderbeg* was released, chronicling the life and fight of the medieval Albanian hero Skanderbeg.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] It went on to win an international prize at the 1954 Cannes Film Festival.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] In 2003, the Tirana International Film Festival was established, the largest film festival in the country.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The Durrës Amphitheatre hosts the Durrës International Film Festival, the country's second largest film festival.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] After the fall of communism in 1991, human resources in sciences and technology in Albania have drastically decreased.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] As of various reports, during 1991 to 2005 approximately 50% of the professors and scientists of the universities and science institutions in the country have left Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Albania was ranked 67th in the Global Innovation Index in 2025.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Telecommunication represents one of the fastest growing and dynamic sectors in Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Vodafone Albania, Telekom Albania and Albtelecom are the three large providers of mobile and internet in Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] As of the Electronic and Postal Communications Authority (AKEP) in 2018, the country had approximately 2.7 million active mobile users with almost 1.8 million active broadband subscribers.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Vodafone Albania alone served more than 931,000 mobile users, Telekom Albania had about 605,000 users and Albtelecom had more than 272,000 users.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] In January 2023, Albania launched its first two satellites, *Albania 1* and *Albania 2*, into orbit, in what was regarded as a milestone effort in monitoring the country's territory and identifying illegal activities.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Albanian-American engineer Mira Murati, the Chief Technology Officer of research organisation OpenAI, played a substantial role in the development and launch of artificial intelligence services such as ChatGPT, Codex and DALL-E.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] In December 2023, Prime Minister Edi Rama announced plans for collaboration between the Albanian government and ChatGPT, facilitated by discussions with Murati.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Rama emphasised the intention to streamline the alignment of Albanian laws with the regulations of the European Union, aiming to reduce costs associated with translation and legal services.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The demographic statistics of Albania, as revealed by the 2023 census conducted by the Instituti i Statistikave (INSTAT), indicated a population of 2,402,113, with a notable decline from the 2,821,977 recorded in the 2011 census.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The decrease in inhabitants began after the disintegration of the communist regime in Albania and is associated with significant shifts within the political, economic, and social structure of Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] A principal factor in this transition incorporates a decline in fertility rates coupled with an increase in emigration, both contributing to persistent demographic changes and challenges.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] It is forecast that the population will continue shrinking for the next decade at least, depending on the actual rates and the level of migration.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Currently, the population density of Albania is measured at 83.6 inhabitants per square kilometer with a varied distribution of inhabitants across different regions.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The counties of Tirana and Durrës showcase substantial concentrations of people, accounting for about 41% of the overall demographic of Albania, with 32% residing in Tirana and 9% in Durrës.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Conversely, more peripheral and rural counties such as Gjirokastër and Kukës present significantly lower population densities, with each aiding 3% to the overall population.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Historically, the Albanian people have established several communities in many regions throughout Southern Europe.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The Albanian diaspora has been formed since the late Middle Ages, when they emigrated to escape either various socio-political difficulties or the Ottoman conquest of Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Following the fall of communism, large numbers of Albanians have migrated to countries such as Australia, Canada, Switzerland, the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Albanian minorities are present in the neighbouring territories such as the west of North Macedonia, the southeast of Montenegro, Kosovo in its entirety and parts of southern Serbia.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Altogether, the number of ethnic Albanians living abroad is estimated to be higher than the total population inside Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] As much as a third of those born in the country's borders now live outside of it, making Albania one of the countries with the highest rate of outmigration relative to its population in the world.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] In 2022 the birth rate was 20% lower than in 2021, largely due to emigration of people of childbearing age.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Subsequent to the collapse of communism in 1991, Albania has undergone a remarkable transformation in its urban landscape, emerging as one of the fastest urbanising countries in Europe.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] At the forefront of this transformation is the Tirana–Durrës agglomeration, a densely populated urban corridor situated along the western coast of Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] This corridor has become the primary locus of population growth and settlement development, attracting a significant influx of internal migrants from the country's peripheral areas.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Despite an overall decline of the country's total population, the proportion of the urban demographic has consistently progressed from 47% in 2001 to 65% in 2023.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] This sustained increase, coupled with the concentration in the Tirana-Durrës region, has led to a spread of regional imbalances, with the peripheral areas, particularly Dibër and Kukës, experiencing severe depopulation.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The official language of the country is Albanian which is spoken by the vast majority of the country's population.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Its standard spoken and written form is revised and merged from the two main dialects, Gheg and Tosk, though it is notably based more on the Tosk dialect.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The Shkumbin river is the rough dividing line between the two dialects.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Among minority languages, Greek is the second most-spoken language in the country, with 0.5 to 3% of the population speaking it as first language, mainly in the country's south where its speakers are concentrated.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Other languages spoken by ethnic minorities in Albania include Aromanian, Serbo-Croatian, Macedonian, Bulgarian, Gorani, and Roma.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Macedonian is official in the Pustec Municipality in East Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] In the 2023 population census, 91.07% reported Albanian as the language spoken at home.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] 1.54% declared to speak at home another language, 0.57% multiple languages, 1.21% gave no answer and 5.59% were unavailable.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Among young people aged 25 or less, English, German and Turkish have seen rising interest after 2000.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Italian and French have had a stable interest, while Greek has lost much of its previous interest.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The trends are linked with cultural and economic factors.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] In the mid-2010s, an increasing number of Albanians showed interest in learning the German language, which has been explained as part of "a Western Balkan trend of preparing to integrate into the German labor market".
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Some of them have gone to Germany for studies or work.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Albania and Germany have agreements for cooperating in helping young people of the two countries know both cultures better.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Due to a sharp rise in economic relations with Turkey, interest in learning Turkish, in particular among young people, was also growing on a yearly basis in the 2010s.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Designated national and cultural minorities in Albania include Aromanian, Greek, Macedonian, Montenegrin, Serb, Roma, Egyptian, Bosnian and Bulgarian peoples, as well as Gorani and Jews as other minority groups.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Albania is a secular and religiously diverse country with no official religion.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Freedom of religion, belief and conscience are guaranteed under the country's constitution.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Albania is nevertheless ranked among the least religious countries in the world.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Religion constitute an important role in the lives of only 39% of the country's population.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] In another report, 56% considered themselves religious, 30% considered themselves non-religious, while 9% defined themselves as convinced atheists.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The Muslim Albanians are spread throughout the country.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Orthodox and Bektashis are mostly found in the south, whereas Catholics mainly live in the north.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] In 2008, there were 694 Catholic churches and 425 Orthodox churches, 568 mosques and 70 bektashi takyas in the country.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] During modern times, the Albanian republican, monarchic and later communist regimes followed a systematic policy of separating religion from official functions and cultural life.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The country has never had an official religion either as a republic or as a kingdom.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] In the 20th century, the clergy of all faiths was weakened under the monarchy and ultimately eradicated during the 1950s and 1960s, under the state policy of obliterating all organised religion from the territories of Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The communist regime persecuted and suppressed religious observance and institutions and entirely banned religion.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The country was then officially declared to be the world's first atheist state.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Religious freedom has returned, however, since the end of communism.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Islam survived communist era persecution and reemerged in the modern era as a practised religion in Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Some smaller Christian sects in Albania include Evangelicals and several Protestant communities including Seventh-day Adventist Church, Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints and Jehovah's Witnesses.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The first recorded Protestant of Albania was Said Toptani, who travelled around Europe and returned to Tirana in 1853, where he preached Protestantism.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The first evangelical Protestants appeared in the 19th century and the Evangelical Alliance was founded in 1892.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Nowadays, it has 160 member congregations from different Protestant denominations.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Following mass emigration to Israel after the fall of communism, there are only 200 Albanian Jews left in the country.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] In Albania, education is secular, free, compulsory, and based on three levels.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The academic year is apportioned into two semesters, beginning in September or October and ending in June or July.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Albanian is the primary language of instruction in the country's academic institutions.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The study of a first foreign language is mandatory and taught most often at elementary and bilingual schools.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Languages taught in schools are English, Italian, French and German.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Albania has a school life expectancy of 16 years and a literacy rate of 98.7%, with 99.2% for men and 98.3% for women.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Compulsory primary education is divided into two levels, elementary and secondary school, from grade one to five and six to nine, respectively.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Pupils are required to attend school from the age six until they turn 16.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Upon successful completion of primary education, all pupils are entitled to attend high schools, specialising in any field, including arts, sports, languages, sciences, and technology.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Tertiary education is optional and has undergone a thorough reformation and restructuring in compliance with the principles of the Bologna Process.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] There are a significant number of private and public institutions of higher education in Albania's major cities.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Tertiary education is organised into three successive levels, the bachelor, master, and doctorate.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The constitution of Albania guarantees its citizens equal, free, and universal health care.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The health care system is organised into primary, secondary, and tertiary healthcare, and is in a process of modernisation and development.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The life expectancy at birth in Albania is 77.8 years, ranking 37th in the world and surpassing several developed countries.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The average healthy life expectancy is 68.8 years, ranking 37th in the world.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] The country's infant mortality rate was estimated at 12 per 1,000 live births in 2015.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] In 2000, the country had the world's 55th-best healthcare performance, as defined by the World Health Organisation (WHO).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Cardiovascular disease is the principal cause of death in Albania, accounting for 52% of deaths.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Accidents, injuries, malignant and respiratory diseases are other primary causes of death.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Neuropsychiatric disease has also increased due to recent demographic, social, and economic changes in the country.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] In 2009, Albania had a fruit and vegetable supply of 886 grams per capita per day, the fifth-highest supply in Europe.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] Compared to other developed and developing countries, Albania has a relatively low rate of obesity, probably thanks to the Mediterranean diet.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p03] According to 2016 WHO data, 21.7% of adults in the country are clinically overweight, with a Body mass index (BMI) score of 25 or more.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] The red and black national colours are displayed on the flag of Albania that is adorned with a double-headed eagle as the foremost recognised national symbol of Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] With the black eagle portraying bravery and strength, the red field symbolises the fortitude and sacrifices of the Albanian people.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] The eagle is linked with the legacy of the national hero Gjergj Kastrioti, renowned as Skanderbeg, who led a prosperous resistance movement against Ottoman rule.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Rooted in the Middle Ages, it emerged as a heraldic symbol in the Principality of Arbër and among notable Albanian dynasties such as the Dukagjini, Kastrioti, Muzaka and Thopia clans.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Amid the Albanian Renaissance, marking the resurgence of Albanian national identity and aspirations for independence, the Albanian eagle regained its prominence.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Its importance reached its culmination with Albania's declaration of independence in 1912, when Ismail Qemali raised it as the national flag in Vlorë.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] The coat of arms of Albania is an adaptation of the flag of Albania and the seal of Skanderbeg.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] The coat comprises the black double-headed eagle positioned at the centre of a red field.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Above the eagle, it carries the helmet of Skanderbeg that is crowned with the head of a golden horned goat.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Ti Shqipëri, më jep nder, më jep emrin Shqipëtar, which translates to "You Albania, give me honour, give me the name Albanian", is the national motto of Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] It finds its foundation in the legacy of national poet Naim Frashëri, who held a renowned role during the Albanian Renaissance.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] The national anthem of Albania, "Himni i Flamurit", was composed by Asdreni and adopted as such following Albania's independence in 1912.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Albanian traditional clothing, with its contrasting variations for the northern Gheg and southern Tosk Albanians, is a testament to Albania's history, cultural diversity and ethnic identity.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Gheg men wear a light-colored shirt paired with wide loose-fitting trousers referred to as the Tirq.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] These trousers are securely fastened by a wide woven belt, the Brez.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] An integral component of their costume is the Xhamadan, a woolen red velvet vest adorned with folkloric motifs and gold patterns.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] They also wear a distinctive dome-shaped hat known as the Qeleshe, crafted from wool, with its origins tracing back to the Illyrians.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Conversely, Tosk men opt for the Fustanella, a knee-length garment designated as the national costume, typically white with pleats, accompanied by a white shirt.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] They also wear a beige or dark blue Xhamadan reminiscent of the Gheg attire.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] To complete their attire, men wear knee-high socks referred to as Çorape and leather shoes known as Opinga.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] The attire of Gheg and Tosk women is renowned for its rich palette of colors and intricate filigree detailing, displayed across various components including ear ornaments, finger rings, necklaces, belt buckles and buttons.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Key components include a long, light-toned shirt paired with an apron, often accompanied by a woolen or felt mantle referred to as the Xhoka.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Additional upper garments, such as the Dollama or Mintan, may be layered, along with a headscarf known as Kapica or Shall.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] A distinctive variation incorporates a pair of aprons, including the Pështjellak at the rear and the Paranik at the front.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Integral to the traditional attire of Gheg women is the ancient Xhubleta.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Dedicated efforts have been undertaken to preserve and promote the dress, acknowledging its significance as an emblem of Albanian heritage.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] As a testament to its importance, the Xhubleta has been inscribed on the UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage List.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] The distinctive bell-shaped garment is fashioned in black and enriched with embroidered ethnic Albanian motifs, showcasing the remarkable craftsmanship of northern Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Its crafting process involves multiple intricate stages, encompassing the preparation of shajak fabric and the precise cutting techniques.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] The artistic history of Albania has been particularly influenced by a multitude of ancient and medieval people, traditions and religions.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] It covers a broad spectrum with mediums and disciplines that include painting, pottery, sculpture, ceramics and architecture all of them exemplifying a great variety in style and shape, in different regions and period.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] The rise of the Byzantine and Ottoman Empire in the Middle Ages was accompanied by a corresponding growth in Christian and Islamic art in the lands of Albania which are apparent in examples of architecture and mosaics throughout the country.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Centuries later, the Albanian Renaissance proved crucial to the emancipation of the modern Albanian culture and saw unprecedented developments in all fields of literature and art whereas artists sought to return to the ideals of Impressionism and Romanticism.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] However, Onufri, Kolë Idromeno, David Selenica, Kostandin Shpataraku and the Zografi Brothers are the most eminent representatives of Albanian art.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] The architecture of Albania reflects the legacy of various civilisations tracing back to the classical antiquity.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Major cities in Albania have evolved from within the castle to include dwellings, religious and commercial structures, with constant redesigning of town squares and evolution of building techniques.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Nowadays, the cities and towns reflect a whole spectrum of various architectural styles.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] In the 20th century, many historical as well as sacred buildings bearing the ancient influence were demolished during the communist era.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Ancient architecture is found throughout Albania and most visible in Byllis, Amantia, Phoenice, Apollonia, Butrint, Antigonia, Shkodër and Durrës.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Considering the long period of rule of the Byzantine Empire, they introduced castles, citadels, churches and monasteries with spectacular wealth of visible murals and frescos.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Perhaps the best known examples can be found in the southern Albanian cities and surroundings of Korçë, Berat, Voskopojë and Gjirokastër.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Involving the introduction of Ottoman architecture there was a development of mosques and other Islamic buildings, particularly seen in Berat and Gjirokastër.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] A productive period of Historicism, Art Nouveau and Neoclassicism merged into the 19th century, best exemplified in Korçë.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] The 20th century brought new architectural styles such as the modern Italian style, which is present in Tirana such as the Skanderbeg Square and Ministries.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] It is also present in Shkodër, Vlorë, Sarandë and Durrës.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Moreover, other towns received their present-day Albania-unique appearance through various cultural or economic influences.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Socialist classicism arrived during the communist era in Albania after the Second World War.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] At this period many socialist-styled complexes, wide roads and factories were constructed, while town squares were redesigned and numerous of historic and important buildings demolished.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Notable examples of that style include the Mother Teresa Square, Pyramid of Tirana, Palace of Congresses and so on.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Three Albanian archaeological sites are included in the list of UNESCO World Heritage Sites.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] These include the ancient remains of Butrint, the medieval Historic Centres of Berat and Gjirokastër, and Natural and Cultural Heritage of the Ohrid region site shared with North Macedonia since 2019.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Furthermore, the royal Illyrian tombs, the remains of Apollonia, the ancient Amphitheatre of Durrës and the Fortress of Bashtovë has been included on the tentative list of Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Albanian folk music is a prominent part of the national identity, and continues to play a major part in overall Albanian music.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Folk music can be divided into two stylistic groups, mainly the northern Gheg varieties, and southern Lab and Tosk varieties.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Northern and southern traditions are contrasted by a rugged tone from the north, and the more relaxed southern form of music.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Many songs concern events from Albanian history and culture, including traditional themes of honour, hospitality, treachery, and revenge.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] The first compilation of Albanian folk music was made by two Himariot musicians, Neço Muka and Koço Çakali, in Paris, during their work with Albanian soprano Tefta Tashko-Koço.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Several gramophone compilations were recorded at the time by the three artists, which eventually led to the recognition of Albanian iso-polyphony as a UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Festivali i Këngës is a traditional Albanian song contest organised by the national broadcaster Radio Televizioni Shqiptar (RTSH).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] The festival is celebrated annually since its inauguration in 1962 and has launched the careers of some of Albania's most successful singers including Vaçe Zela and Parashqevi Simaku.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] It is significantly a music competition among Albanian performers presenting unreleased songs in premiere, composed by Albanian authors and voted by juries or by public.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Contemporary artists Rita Ora, Bebe Rexha, Era Istrefi, Dua Lipa, Ava Max, Bleona, Elvana Gjata, Ermonela Jaho, and Inva Mula have achieved international recognition for their music, while soprano Ermonela Jaho has been described by some as the "world's most acclaimed soprano".
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Albanian opera singer Saimir Pirgu was nominated for the 2017 Grammy Award.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] The cultural renaissance was first of all expressed through the development of the Albanian language in the area of church texts and publications.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] The Protestant reforms invigorated hopes for the development of the local language and literary tradition, when cleric Gjon Buzuku translated the Catholic liturgy into Albanian, trying to do for Albanian what Martin Luther had done for German.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Meshari (*The Missal*) written by Gjon Buzuku was published in 1555 and is considered one of the first literary work of written Albanian during the Middle Ages.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] The refined level of the language and the stabilised orthography must be the result of an earlier tradition of written Albanian, a tradition that is not well understood.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] However, there is some fragmented evidence, pre-dating Buzuku, which indicates that Albanian was written from at least the 14th century.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Albanian writings from these centuries must not have been religious texts only, but historical chronicles too.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] The *History of Skanderbeg* is still the foundation of Skanderbeg studies and is considered an Albanian cultural treasure, vital to the formation of Albanian national self-consciousness.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] The most famous Albanian writer in the 20th and 21st century is probably Ismail Kadare.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Throughout the centuries, Albanian cuisine has been widely influenced by Albanian culture, geography and history, and as such, different parts of the country enjoy specific regional cuisines.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Cooking traditions especially vary between the north and the south, owing to differing topography and climate that essentially contribute to the excellent growth conditions for a wide array of herbs, fruits, and vegetables.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Albanians produce and use many varieties of fruits such as lemons, oranges, figs, and most notably, olives, which are perhaps the most important element of Albanian cooking.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Spices and other herbs such as basil, lavender, mint, oregano, rosemary, and thyme are widely used, as are vegetables such as garlic, onions, peppers, potatoes, tomatoes, as well as legumes of all types.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] With a coastline along the Adriatic and Ionian in the Mediterranean Sea, fish, crustaceans, and seafood are a popular and an integral part of the Albanian diet.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Otherwise, lamb is the traditional meat for different holidays and religious festivals for both Christians and Muslims, although poultry, beef, and pork are also in plentiful supply.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Tavë kosi ("soured milk casserole") is the national dish of Albania, consisting of lamb and rice baked under a thick, tart veil of yoghurt.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Fërgesë is another national dish, made up of peppers, tomatoes, and cottage cheese.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Pite is also popular, a baked pastry with a filling of a mixture of spinach and gjizë (curd) or mish (ground meat).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Petulla, a traditional fried dough, is also a popular speciality, and is served with powdered sugar or feta cheese and different sorts of fruit jams.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Flia consists of multiple crêpe-like layers brushed with cream and served with sour cream.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Krofne, similar to Berliner doughnuts, are filled with jam, or chocolate and often eaten during winter.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Coffee is an integral part of the Albanian lifestyle.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] The country has more coffee houses per capita than any other country in the world.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Tea is also enjoyed both at home or outside at cafés, bars, or restaurants. Çaj Mali (Sideritis tea) is enormously beloved, and a part of the daily routine for most Albanians.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] It is cultivated across Southern Albania and noted for its medicinal properties.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Albanian wine is also common throughout the country, and has been cultivated for thousands of years.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Albania has a long and ancient history of wine production, and belongs to the Old World of wine producing countries.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Albania participated at the Olympic Games in 1972 for the first time.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] The country made their Winter Olympic Games debut in 2006.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Albania missed the next four games, two of them due to the 1980 and 1984 boycotts, but returned for the 1992 games in Barcelona.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Since then, Albania have participated in all games.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Albania normally competes in events that include swimming, athletics, weightlifting, shooting and wrestling.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] The country have been represented by the National Olympic Committee of Albania since 1972.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] The nation has participated at the Mediterranean Games since the games of 1987 in Syria.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] The Albanian athletes have won a total of 43 (8 gold, 17 silver and 18 bronze) medals from 1987 to 2013.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Popular sports in Albania include football, weightlifting, basketball, volleyball, tennis, swimming, rugby union and gymnastics.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Football is by far the most popular sport in Albania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] It is governed by the Football Association of Albania (Albanian: *Federata Shqiptare e Futbollit*, F.SH.F.), which has membership in FIFA and UEFA.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Albania scored their first ever goal in a major tournament and secured their first ever win in European Championship when they beat Romania by 1–0 in a UEFA Euro 2016 match on 19 June 2016.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] The most successful football clubs are Skënderbeu, KF Tirana, Dinamo Tirana, Partizani and Vllaznia.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Weightlifting is one of the most successful individual sports for the Albanians, with the national team winning medals at the European Weightlifting Championships and the rest international competitions.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] Albanian weightlifters have won a total of 16 medals at the European Championships with one of them being gold, seven silver and eight bronze.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/albania-p04] In the World Weightlifting Championships, the Albanian weightlifting team has won in 1972 a gold, in 2002 a silver, and in 2011 a bronze medal.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko is a Legend of the Australian Football Hall of Fame, and as a player was known for his versatility, uncanny balance and spectacular marking.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] He immortalised his reputation in the game by taking the most iconic mark in football history in the 1970 VFL Grand Final.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] In 2009 *The Australian* nominated Jesaulenko as one of the 25 greatest footballers never to win a Brownlow Medal.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Recruited from Canberra, Jesaulenko has played more games and kicked more goals than any other player from the Australian Capital Territory.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] He represented his home territory in 1978.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] His popularity caused the code to surge in popularity there, and he remains a household name in the ACT.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] He remains to date the only Carlton footballer to have kicked 100 or more goals in a season, and the last player-coach to win a VFL/AFL premiership (1979).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] In 2002, he was inducted into the Ukrainian Sports Hall of Fame.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] On 20 October 2010, he was inducted into the Sport Australia Hall of Fame.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] In July 2013, Jesaulenko was named captain of the first Australia Post Multicultural Team of Champions.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] In January 2022, Jesaulenko was diagnosed with Parkinson's disease.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko was born in Salzburg, then Allied-occupied Austria.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] His father, Vasil, was Ukrainian and served as a German policeman during World War II.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] His mother, Vera, was born in Russia, and she had survived the horrors of seeing her father shot dead by German soldiers and having her first child, whom she first gave the name Alex, taken away from her when she was in a German prison camp.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] The child was not heard of again until over fifty years later.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Along with many other Eastern Europeans who were World War II refugees or displaced persons, the Jesaulenkos emigrated to Australia via the Norwegian passenger ship *SS Skaugum*.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] They arrived in the port of Melbourne on 28 July 1949.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] They spent the first six months living at the Bonegilla Migrant Reception and Training Centre.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] According to Jesaulenko, the family name should have been spelt *Esaulenko*, but immigration officials listed "Esaulenko" with a "J" in front, thinking that they had heard a "J" in his name.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] From there, the family moved to Canberra, where Vasil set up shop as a carpenter-cabinetmaker.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] The young Jesaulenko was enrolled at St Edmund's College and then Telopea Park High, where he played soccer and rugby union.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] He did not start playing Australian rules football until he was 14 years old.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] He began playing at the Eastlake Football Club in Canberra.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko has credited his time at Eastlake for instilling in him a winning culture.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] After breaking into the senior team, he quickly established himself as a star, playing in three consecutive premierships for Eastlake from 1964 to 1966.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko made his senior VFL debut in the opening round of the 1967 season against Fitzroy at Princes Park, where he had 14 touches and kicked two goals in a 94-point victory.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] He would play every game for Carlton that season, one of four players to do so.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] In that season's Brownlow Medal count, he would poll 15 votes to finish third behind eventual winner Ross Smith (24 votes) from St Kilda and North Melbourne's Laurie Dwyer (17 votes).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko would go on to play in four Carlton premierships – in 1968, 1970, 1972 and 1979.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko was selected for All-Australian honours in 1969 and 1972.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] He also has the dubious record at Carlton for the most inaccurate score of 5 goals and 12 behinds, against Hawthorn in 1969.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] In December 1969, Jesaulenko put an end to newspaper rumours that he might leave Carlton and either play football in Western Australia or return to Canberra.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] It was well known that he was working as a barman at a Melbourne hotel at the time, and was receiving little more than the "average" player.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] A spectacular and popular player, Jesaulenko was renowned for his high marking, mercurial ground play, superb balance and goalkicking.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] He kicked 115 goals in the 1970 season, breaking the club record and becoming the first (and, as of 2021, only) player to kick more than 100 goals in a season for Carlton.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] He went on to play in the famous 1970 VFL Grand Final against Collingwood.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] In front of an all-time record MCG crowd of 121,696 fans, Carlton came from a 44-point deficit at half-time to win by 10 points.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko's marking skill was perhaps best highlighted by a spectacular mark over big Collingwood ruckman Graeme Jenkin in the 1970 VFL Grand Final.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] The commentary has Mike Williamson shouting the now-famous phrase: *"Oh, Jesaulenko, you beauty!"*.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] This "specky" is acclaimed by some to be the "Mark of the Century", and it was the first to be recognised officially as the Mark of the Year; the medal awarded to the annual winner is called the Alex Jesaulenko Medal.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko has downplayed the specky, citing other marks he took—even during the same game—as greater feats.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] He later said: "The images make it look classical, like it was taken from the marking manual, ...
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] For a brief period in 1977, Jesaulenko wrote a weekly Tuesday column for *The Canberra Times* called 'Jezza on Rules'.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko's vision would be realised 13 years later when the VFL became the Australian Football League.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] The 1978 VFL season began dreadfully for Carlton.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] After finishing top of the ladder in 1976 but losing the Preliminary Final by one point and then losing in the last round of the home-and-away season to miss out on the finals in 1977, they had brought Ian Stewart over from South Melbourne to replace Ian Thorogood as senior coach.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] By Round 6, they had only won one game and were sitting second-last on the ladder, and Stewart had gone.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Carlton president George Harris turned to Sergio Silvagni to fill the void while a long-term replacement was being sought, but on the suggestion of media personality Michael Williamson, Harris gave the job to Jesaulenko.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko's sporting achievements were recognised outside the football world as well; he was included in the 1979 New Year Honours list as a Member (Civil) of the Order of the British Empire "for service to the sport of Australian Rules football".
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko continued on as Carlton's captain-coach in 1979.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] With a superb support cast, the Blues took out the minor premiership with 19 wins and also set a new VFL record for the largest-scoring aggregate in a home-and-away season (2,772 points).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] In the second quarter of the Round 10 match against Collingwood at Princes Park, Jesaulenko was running back with the flight of the ball when he was met heavily by Stan Magro, resulting in concussion and a shoulder injury.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] The Blues were trailing by 25 points at that stage, but they rallied and fought back with a strong second half to win by 16 points.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Amazingly, Jesaulenko was back in action just two weeks later in the Round 12 game against Geelong at Kardinia Park; trailing by 30 points at the last change, Carlton almost pulled off a great comeback, eventually falling short by six points.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] After the 43-point win against Essendon in Round 15 at Princes Park, in which he had 22 touches and kicked a goal, Jesaulenko missed the next six games with what was later revealed to be a back injury; he had suffered damage to his sciatic nerve which had caused him to lose feeling in his right leg.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] He underwent a daily 30-minute exercise routine to strengthen his stomach and back muscles, returning to on-field action in time for the final round of the home-and-away season against South Melbourne at Princes Park.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko was, in fact, the last player-coach in the VFL/AFL to win a premiership, and he is likely to remain so indefinitely.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko had pay disputes with Carlton in 1977.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Subsequently, he tied his ongoing presence at the club to then-Carlton club president George Harris.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] At the end of the 1979 season, despite the premiership, Harris was ousted from his position as President of Carlton Football Club, and Jesaulenko walked out on Carlton and resigned from the club.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] In a deal managed by trucking multimillionaire (now billionaire) and St Kilda club president Lindsay Fox, Jesaulenko moved to the St Kilda Football Club in 1980.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] While initially appointed as an on-field player only, Jesaulenko was then appointed playing coach when the incumbent St Kilda senior coach, Mike Patterson, was sacked by Fox after Round 2.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] He played 23 games and kicked 20 goals for the Saints in 1980–1981 and stayed on for a further season as senior coach.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko retired as a player after Round 8 on 16 May 1981.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] He was the last person to serve as captain-coach in the VFL; however, Malcolm Blight was a player-coach at North Melbourne until Round 16 of the same season but was not captain during this time.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] After leaving St Kilda, Jesaulenko went north to serve as captain-coach of Sandgate in the then-Queensland Football League.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] He retired at the end of 1984 after Sandgate lost their semi-final, after which he moved into the hotel business in Queensland for several years.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] In the first half of the 1989 VFL season, Carlton was in disarray when communication had almost completely broken down between the players and senior coach Robert Walls, who only two seasons prior had guided the Blues to the flag.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Carlton had fallen one game short of the Grand Final in 1988 but started the 1989 season with five straight losses.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] The defining point came after losing to the Brisbane Bears by three points in Round 10 at home, with Warwick Capper kicking the winning goal after the siren.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] At that stage, the Blues were second-last on the ladder with only two wins and in danger of "winning" their first-ever wooden spoon.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Walls was sacked as Carlton Football Club senior coach two days after the match.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko had not been back at Carlton since his acrimonious departure almost a decade earlier, when he was appointed caretaker senior coach of Carlton for the remainder of the 1989 season.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko's optimism appeared to rub off on the Carlton players; they beat Sydney by 28 points and would win six more games to finish eighth.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko stepped down as Carlton Football Club senior coach at the end of the 1990 season and was replaced by David Parkin, who returned in his second stint as Carlton senior coach.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] His last coaching appointment, at Coburg for the 1993 season, was a total disaster, with the Lions losing all eighteen games during a losing sequence of thirty games in the dying days of the Victorian Football Association.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] When Carlton set up their Hall of Fame in 1987, Jesaulenko was one of the inaugural inductees.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] He was also an inaugural inductee into the Australian Football Hall of Fame in 1996, and in 2008 was elevated to Legend status.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] In 1996, he was also named on the half-forward flank in the AFL Team of the Century.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] In 1997, he was inducted as an official Legend of the Carlton Football Club.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] When the Carlton Team of the Century was announced, Jesaulenko was also named on the half-forward flank.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Upon being elevated to Legend status in the Australian Football Hall of Fame, Jesaulenko was accorded tribute from the great contemporaries of his era.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] After retiring from football, Jesaulenko worked for billionaire and noted Carlton patron Richard Pratt at his recycling firm Visy for 15 years in the sales and public relations department.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] When it was known that Pratt was in his last days in April 2009, Jesaulenko contemplated paying him a farewell visit at his mansion, but thought better of it lest he attracted too much attention.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] During the 1970s, when people spoke about football, it was common for people to refer to taking a high mark as "taking a Jezza".
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Be in it.* advertisement, the character "Norm" says "Beauty, Jezza" while watching football.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko is mentioned in the 1985 song "The Back Upon Which Jezza Jumped" by Melbourne band TISM (This Is Serious, Mum), appearing on the band's self-titled demo tape.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] The song depicts Graeme "Jerker" Jenkin being left to be forgotten because of Jezza's spectacular mark.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] The main character in the Australian children's book *Jezza* is a dog named after Alex Jesaulenko.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] "Ordinary dogs chase tennis balls or fetch silly sticks.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] My new family called me Jezza because that was the name of a famous footballer.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] I don't mean to brag, but I'm quite a footballer too." (Bell, 1991).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/alex-jesaulenko] In 2012, singer-songwriter Tex Perkins wrote and performed "Jesaulenko You Beauty" exclusively for *The Marngrook Footy Show*.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The ancestors of Aboriginal Australians began arriving from Southeast Asia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, during the Last Glacial Period.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] By the time of British settlement, Aboriginal Australians spoke more than 250 distinct languages and had one of the oldest living cultures in the world.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia's written history commenced with Dutch exploration of most of the coastline in the 17th century.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] British colonisation began in 1788 with the establishment of the penal colony of New South Wales.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] By the mid-19th century, most of the continent had been explored by European settlers and five additional self-governing British colonies were established, each gaining responsible government by 1890.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The colonies federated in 1901, forming the Commonwealth of Australia.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] This continued a process of increasing autonomy from the United Kingdom, highlighted by the *Statute of Westminster Adoption Act 1942*, and culminating in the *Australia Act 1986*.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia is a parliamentary democracy with a constitutional monarchy, and a federation comprising six states and ten territories.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Its population of almost 29 million is highly urbanised and heavily concentrated on the eastern seaboard.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Canberra is the nation's capital, while its most populous cities are Sydney and Melbourne, each with a population of more than five million.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia's culture is diverse, and the country has one of the highest foreign-born populations in the world.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] It has a highly developed economy and one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Its abundant natural resources and well-developed international trade relations are crucial to the country's economy.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] It ranks highly for quality of life, health, education, economic freedom, civil liberties and political rights.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, and has the world's thirteenth-highest military expenditure.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] It is a member of international groups including: the United Nations, the G20, the OECD, the World Trade Organization, Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community and the Commonwealth of Nations.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia also participates in the defence, intelligence and security alliances ANZUS, AUKUS and Five Eyes.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] It is a major non-NATO ally of the United States.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The name *Australia* (pronounced /əˈstreɪliə/ in Australian English) is derived from the Latin *Terra Australis Incognita* ('unknown southern land'), a name used for a hypothetical continent in the Southern Hemisphere since ancient times.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Several 16th-century cartographers used the word *Australia* on maps, but not to identify modern Australia.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] When the Dutch began visiting and mapping Australia in the 17th century, they called the continent *New Holland*.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The name *Australia* was popularised by the explorer Matthew Flinders, who circumnavigated the continent in 1803.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] However, when his account of his voyage was published in 1814, the name *Terra Australis* was used.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Governor of New South Wales Lachlan Macquarie officially recommended the name *Australia* to replace *New Holland* in December 1817.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The British Admiralty adopted the name in 1824, and the British Parliament used it in legislation in 1828.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The United Kingdom Hydrographic Office used the new name in *The Australia Directory* of 1830.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The name "Commonwealth of Australia" for the new federation of the six former colonies was formalised in the *Commonwealth of Australia Constitution Act 1900* (UK).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Colloquial names for Australia include "Oz", "Straya" and "Down Under".
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Human habitation of the Australian continent is estimated to have begun 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, with the migration of people by land bridges and short sea crossings from what is now Southeast Asia.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] It is uncertain how many waves of immigration may have contributed to these ancestors of modern Aboriginal Australians.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The Madjedbebe rock shelter in Arnhem Land is possibly the oldest site showing the presence of humans in Australia.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The oldest human remains found are the Lake Mungo remains, which have been dated to approximately 42,000 years ago.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australian culture is one of the oldest continuous cultures on Earth.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] At the time of first European contact, Aboriginal Australians belonged to wide range of societies, with diverse economies spread across at least 250 different language groups.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Estimates of the Aboriginal population before British settlement range from 300,000 to 3 million.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australians cultures were (and remain) deeply connected with the land and the environment, with stories of The Dreaming maintained through oral tradition, songs, dance and paintings.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Certain groups engaged in fire-stick farming, fish farming, and built semi-permanent shelters.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] These practices have variously been characterised as "hunter-gatherer", "agricultural", "natural cultivation" and "intensification".
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Torres Strait Islander people first settled their islands at least 2,500 years ago.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Culturally and linguistically distinct from mainland Aboriginal peoples, they were seafarers and obtained their livelihood from seasonal horticulture and the resources of their reefs and seas.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Agriculture also developed on some islands and villages appeared by the 1300s.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] By the mid-18th century in northern Australia, contact, trade and cross-cultural engagement had been established between local Aboriginal groups and Makassan trepangers, visiting from present-day Indonesia.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] In 1606 the crew of the Dutch ship, *Duyfken*, captained by Willem Janszoon, made the first documented European landing in Australia and contact with Aboriginal Australians.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Later that year, Luís Vaz de Torres sailed to the north of Australia through Torres Strait, along New Guinea's southern coast.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Abel Tasman's voyage of 1642 was the first known European expedition to reach Van Diemen's Land.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] On his second voyage of 1644, he mapped the north coast of Australia south of New Guinea.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Following Tasman's voyages, the Dutch were able to make almost complete maps of Australia's northern and western coasts and much of its southern and south-eastern Tasmanian coasts.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] In 1770, Captain James Cook sailed along and mapped the east coast, which he named "New South Wales" and claimed for Great Britain.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] In 1786, the British government announced its intention to establish a penal colony in New South Wales.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] On 26 January 1788, the First Fleet commanded by Captain Arthur Phillip, arrived at Sydney Cove, Port Jackson.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] A camp was established and the Union Flag raised and the date later became Australia's national day.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Most early settlers were convicts, transported for petty crimes and assigned as labourers or servants to "free settlers" (willing immigrants).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Once emancipated, convicts tended to integrate into colonial society.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Aboriginal resistance, convict rebellions and bushranging were sometimes suppressed under martial law.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The 1808 Rum Rebellion, carried out by officers of the New South Wales Corp, led to a temporary military junta.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] During the next two decades, social and economic reforms, together with the establishment of a Legislative Council and Supreme Court, saw the penal colony transition to a civil society.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The indigenous population declined for 150 years following European settlement, mainly due to infectious disease.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] British colonial authorities did not sign any treaties with Aboriginal groups.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] As settlement expanded, tens of thousands of Indigenous people and thousands of settlers were killed in frontier conflicts, which many historians argue included acts of genocide by settlers.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Settlers dispossessed surviving Indigenous peoples of most of their land.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] In 1803, a settlement was established in Van Diemen's Land (present-day Tasmania), and in 1813, Gregory Blaxland, William Lawson and William Wentworth crossed the Blue Mountains west of Sydney, opening the interior to European settlement.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The British claim was extended to the whole Australian continent in 1827 when Major Edmund Lockyer established a settlement on King George Sound (modern-day Albany).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The Swan River Colony (present-day Perth) was established in 1829, evolving into the largest Australian colony by area, Western Australia.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Separate colonies were carved from New South Wales: Tasmania in 1825, South Australia in 1836, Victoria in 1851, and Queensland in 1859.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] South Australia and Victoria were founded as free colonies – they never accepted transported convicts.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Growing opposition to the convict system culminated in its abolition in the eastern colonies by the 1850s.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Initially a free colony, Western Australia accepted convicts from 1850 to 1868.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The six colonies individually gained responsible government between 1855 and 1890, managing most of their own affairs while remaining part of the British Empire.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The Colonial Office in London retained control of some matters, notably foreign affairs.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The colonial parliaments progressively extended voting rights to adult men from 1856, with women's suffrage on equal terms following between the 1890s and 1900s.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Some colonies introduced racial restrictions on voting from 1885.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] In the mid-19th century, explorers such as Burke and Wills charted Australia's interior.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] A series of gold rushes beginning in the early 1850s led to an influx of new migrants from China, North America and continental Europe, as well as outbreaks of bushranging and civil unrest; the latter peaked in 1854 when Ballarat miners launched the Eureka Rebellion against gold licence fees.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The 1860s saw the rise of blackbirding, where South Sea Islanders were coerced or abducted into indentured labour, mainly by Queensland colonists.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] From 1886, Australian colonial governments began removing many Aboriginal children from their families and communities, justified on the grounds of child protection and forced assimilation policies.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The Second Boer War (1899–1902) marked the largest overseas deployment of Australia's colonial forces.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] On 1 January 1901, federation of the colonies was achieved after a decade of planning, constitutional conventions and referendums, resulting in the establishment of the Commonwealth of Australia as a nation under the new Australian Constitution.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] From 1901, Australia was a self-governing dominion within the British Empire.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] It was one of the founding members of the League of Nations in 1920, and the United Nations in 1945.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The *Statute of Westminster 1931* ended the ability of the UK to legislate for Australia at the federal level without Australia's consent.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia adopted it in 1942, but it was backdated to 1939 to confirm the validity of legislation passed during World War II.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The Australian Capital Territory was formed in 1911 as the location for the future federal capital of Canberra.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] While it was being constructed, Melbourne served as the temporary capital from 1901 to 1927.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The Northern Territory was transferred from South Australia to the Commonwealth in 1911.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia took over the administration of the Territory of Papua (previously British New Guinea) in 1905 and of the Territory of New Guinea (formerly German New Guinea) in 1920.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The two were unified as the Territory of Papua and New Guinea in 1949 and gained independence from Australia in 1975.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] In 1914, Australia joined the Allies in the First World War, and took part in the fighting on several fronts.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Of the 324,000 men who served overseas, about 60,000 were killed and another 152,000 were wounded.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Many Australians regard the defeat of the Australian and New Zealand Army Corps (ANZAC) at Gallipoli in 1915 as the "baptism of fire" that forged the new nation's identity.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The beginning of the campaign is commemorated annually on Anzac Day, a date which rivals Australia Day as the nation's most important.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] From 1939 to 1945, Australia joined the Allies in fighting the Second World War.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia's armed forces fought in the Pacific, European and Mediterranean and Middle East theatres.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Since 1951, Australia has maintained a mutual security alliance with the United States under the ANZUS treaty.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] In the three decades following World War II, Australia experienced significant increases in living standards, leisure time and suburban development.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Governments encouraged a large wave of immigration from across Europe and called these migrants "New Australians".
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] High immigration was justified to Australians using the slogan "populate or perish", and from the 1960s the white Australia policy was gradually relaxed.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] A member of the Western Bloc during the Cold War, Australia participated in the Korean War and the Malayan Emergency during the 1950s and the Vietnam War from 1962 to 1973.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Tensions over communist influence in society led to unsuccessful attempts by the Menzies Government to ban the Communist Party of Australia, and a bitter split in the Labor Party in 1955.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] As a result of a 1967 referendum, the federal government gained the power to legislate with regard to Aboriginal Australians, and Aboriginal Australians were fully included in the census.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Pre-colonial land interests (referred to as native title in Australia) was recognised in law for the first time when the High Court of Australia held in *Mabo v Queensland (No 2)* that Australia was not *terra nullius* ('land belonging to no one') at the time of European settlement.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Following the abolition of the last vestiges of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia's demography and culture transformed as a result of a large and ongoing wave of non-European immigration, mostly from Asia.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The late 20th century also saw an increasing focus on foreign policy ties with other Asia–Pacific nations.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The Australia Acts of 1986 severed the remaining constitutional ties between Australia and the United Kingdom while maintaining the monarch in her independent capacity as Queen of Australia.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] In a 1999 constitutional referendum, 55% of voters rejected abolishing the monarchy and becoming a republic.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Following the September 11 attacks in the United States, Australia joined the United States in fighting the Afghanistan War from 2001 to 2021 and the Iraq War from 2003 to 2009.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The nation's trade relations also became increasingly oriented towards East Asia in the 21st century, with China becoming the nation's largest trading partner by a large margin.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] In response to the COVID-19 pandemic, from March 2020 lockdowns and other restrictions on public gatherings and movement across the national and state borders were implemented by the Federal, state and territory governments.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Following the rollout of vaccines in 2021, these restrictions were gradually eased.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] In October 2023, Australia declared that COVID-19 was no longer a communicable disease incident of national significance.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia consists of the mainland Australian continent, the island of Tasmania, numerous smaller offshore islands, and the remote offshore territories of Ashmore and Cartier Islands, Christmas Island, Cocos (Keeling) Islands, Coral Sea Islands, Heard and McDonald Islands, and Norfolk Island.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia also claims about 42% of Antarctica as the Australian Antarctic Territory, but this claim is only recognised by four other countries.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Mainland Australia lies between latitudes 9° and 44° south, and longitudes 112° and 154° east.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Surrounded by the Indian and Pacific oceans, Australia is separated from Asia by the Arafura and Timor seas, with the Coral Sea lying off the Queensland coast, and the Tasman Sea lying between Australia and New Zealand.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The Great Barrier Reef, the world's largest coral reef, lies a short distance off the north-east coast and extends for more than 2,300 km (1,400 mi).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The mainland is the world's smallest continent and the country is the sixth-largest by total area.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia is sometimes considered the world's largest island and is often dubbed the "island continent".
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] It has 35,877 km (22,293 mi) of coastline (excluding all offshore islands), and claims an exclusive economic zone of 8,148,250 square kilometres (3,146,060 sq mi).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] This exclusive economic zone does not include the Australian Antarctic Territory.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] In 2021, Australia had 10% of the global permanent meadows and pastureland.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Forest cover is about 17% of Australia's land area.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The Australian mainland is relatively flat, with an average height of 325 metres (1,066 ft) compared with 870 metres (2,850 ft) for all continents.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The Great Dividing Range runs along most of eastern Australia, dividing the central lowlands from the eastern highlands.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] At 2,228 m (7,310 ft), Mount Kosciuszko is the highest mountain on the mainland.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Taller are Mawson Peak, at 2,745 m (9,006 ft), on Heard Island, and, in the Australian Antarctic Territory, Mount McClintock and Mount Menzies, at 3,492 m (11,457 ft) and 3,355 m (11,007 ft) respectively.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The Murray-Darling is the major river system, draining most of inland New South Wales and Southern Queensland towards Lake Alexandrina and the sea in South Australia.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] There are also smaller coastal river systems, inland drainage systems such as the Lake Eyre system, and salt lake systems in central and western Australia.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia's rivers have the lowest discharge into the sea of any continent.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The mainland's flat, arid profile also makes its rivers slow-moving, resulting in a build up of salt on the land.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Salinisation adversely affects Australia's soil which is, on average, poor in nutrients compared with world standards.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia's population is concentrated on the coastal fringes.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] About 95% of the population lives within 100 km of the coast; the world average is 39%.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia's population density is 3.5 inhabitants per square kilometre, which is one of the lowest in the world.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] However, there is a large concentration of the population in cities along the temperate south-eastern coastline, and population density exceeds 38 inhabitants per square kilometre in central Melbourne.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Formerly part of the Rodinia and Gondwana supercontinents, Australia completely separated from Antarctica about 35 million years ago and continued drifting northwards.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] When the Last Glacial Period ended, rising sea levels separated the Australian mainland from New Guinea about 8,000 years ago and from Tasmania about 6,000 years ago.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia lies well within the Australian tectonic plate.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The mainland is relatively stable geologically, with no major mountain building, active volcanoes or tectonic faults.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] However, the Australian plate is moving north-northeast at a rate of about 6 to 7 cm a year and is currently in collision with the Eurasian plate and Pacific plate.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The resulting intratectonic stresses lead to relatively high seismic activity for a geologically stable landmass.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] There were 18 earthquakes with a moment magnitude of greater than 6 between 1901 and 2017.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The Newcastle earthquake of 1989 was Australia's deadliest, killing 13 people.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] There were active volcanoes on the eastern mainland as recently as 4,600 years ago, and this is reflected in Aboriginal place names and creation stories.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Currently, volcanism occurs in the remote Heard Island and McDonald Islands.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The Australian continental crust was created in three cycles from the oldest Archaean cratons in the west to the younger orogenic formations in the east (built about 541 million to 252 million years ago).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The oldest Australian surface rocks date to the Archaean period.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Some in Western Australia are older than 3.7 billion years and others in South Australia are over 3.1 billion years old.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The oldest zircon crystals on Earth, dating back 4.4 billion years, have been found in Western Australia.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] However, about 80 per cent of Australia is covered by sedimentary rocks and regolith that are less than 250 million years old.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The Australian climate ranges from wet tropical in the northeast and northwest to arid in the centre.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The coastal south is temperate and humid with winter freezing and snow in the southeastern highlands and Tasmania.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The climate is influenced by Australia's position in the "horse latitudes", which tends to bring arid conditions.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Overall, the Australian mainland is the driest inhabited continent, with an average annual rainfall of 470 millimetres (19 in).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] About 70% of the country is arid or semi-arid, and about 18% is desert.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The climate is also influenced by various systems such as the El Niño–Southern Oscillation, the Indian Ocean Dipole and the Southern Annular Mode.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia has unusual variability in rainfall within years and between years, leading to frequent droughts and flooding.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Cyclones and rain depressions are common in tropical Australia.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The summer monsoon brings significant rainfall to northern Australia and low pressure cells bring winter rainfall in the south.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The hottest regions are in the northwest of the country and the coolest in the southeast.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Bushfire conditions are common in southern Australia.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Climate change from increased greenhouse gas emissions has led to a 1.5 °C rise in Australian temperatures since 1910 and an increase in extreme heat and heavy rainfall events.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] There has been a reduction in rainfall from April to October in southern Australia since 1970 and a longer bushfire season since the 1950s.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Rainfall has increased in northern Australia since the 1970s.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The number of tropical cyclones has fallen since 1982 and alpine snow has decreased since the late 1950s.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Sea levels are rising around Australia and the surrounding oceans are becoming more acidic.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia is one of 17 megadiverse countries.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Because of its long geographic isolation, much of Australia's biota is unique.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] About 94% of its amphibians, 93% of its reptiles and flowering plants, 69% of its mammals and 46% of its birds are endemic.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia has a wide range of ecosystems of which 89 regions and 419 subregions are recognised in the Australian bioregion framework.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] In January 2025, there were 168,386 named species on the Australian National Species List.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] However, it is estimated that 70% of Australian species have not been discovered and classified and that there may be 600,000 Australian native species.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] In general, knowledge of vertebrates and flowering plants is better than for invertebrates and fungi.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] It is estimated that less that 10% of Australia's fungi and insects have been named.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] About 10% of the world's known plant species are found in Australia.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Many of these have adapted to the arid climate, variable rainfall and nutrient-poor soil.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Deserts and xeric shrubland cover about 70% of the mainland.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Acacia, banksia and eucalypts have spread over much of Australia.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Many plants have hard and long-living leaves, and are rich in carbon, poor in nutrients, and well adapted to bushfires.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] About two-thirds of the world's 330 species of marsupials are native to Australia.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australian placental mammals (overwhelmingly bats, rats and mice) also make up almost 47% of the world's land mammal species.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia has about 10% of the world's known reptile species.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] There are also about 320,500 invertebrate species, of which insects are the largest class, accounting for more than 75% of all animal species.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia has over 15,000 known species of fungi, although it is possible that tens of thousands more exist.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia's wildlife show many adaptations to their environments.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] As the leaves of most plants are poor in nutrients, Australia has a high proportion of birds, insects and marsupials, such as the honey possum, that feed on nectar and pollen.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The koala is an exception, specialising in feeding on eucalyptus leaves.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Nutritionally poor flora and variable rainfall also favour animals with lower energy requirements, including snakes, lizards, and hopping marsupials such as the kangaroo and wallaby.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] There is, however, evidence of convergent evolution of Australia's marsupials and the placental mammals of other continents living in similar environments.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] For example, the extinct thylacine (Tasmanian tiger) had similarities with the placental wolf, marsupial moles with the golden moles of Africa, and hopping mice with the hopping rodents of other arid regions.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] There were major extinctions of Australia's vertebrates, including its megafauna, about 46 thousand years ago, and there is an ongoing scientific debate over the role of human activity and climate change in these extinctions.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The contraction of the range of the Tasmanian tiger and Tasmanian devil to that island about 4,000 to 5,000 years ago is also consistent with changes on the mainland including an increasing human population, the introduction of the dingo, and the greater use of fire and new stone tool technologies.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Over the past two centuries, Australia has lost more mammal species than any other continent.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Overall, 100 Australian species are listed as extinct or extinct in the wild.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] In June 2021, over 1,000 animal and plant species were listed by Australian governments as endangered or critically endangered.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The major threats to endangered species are landscape change, ecosystem disruption, introduced species such as the feral cat and red fox, and climate change.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The federal *Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999* is the legal framework for the protection of threatened species.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The National Reserve System is Australia's network of protected areas.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] As at 30 June 2022, it covered over 22% of Australia's land mass.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] *Australia's Strategy for Nature 2024–2030* is the national biodiversity plan that aims to reverse biodiversity loss in Australia by 2030 and meet the county's obligations under the United Nations Convention on Biological Diversity and other international agreements.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia is a constitutional monarchy, a parliamentary democracy and a federation.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The country has maintained its mostly unchanged constitution alongside a stable liberal democratic political system since Federation in 1901.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] It is one of the world's oldest federations, in which power is divided between the federal and state governments.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Following elections on 3 May 2025, the prime minister is Anthony Albanese of the Australian Labor Party.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Charles III reigns as King of Australia and is represented in Australia by the governor-general at the federal level and by the governors at the state level, who by section 63 of the Constitution and convention act on the advice of their ministers.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Thus, in practice the governor-general acts as a legal figurehead for the actions of the prime minister and the Cabinet.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The governor-general may in some situations exercise reserve powers: powers exercisable in the absence of, or contrary to, ministerial advice.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] When these powers may be exercised is governed by convention and their precise scope is unclear.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The most notable exercise of these powers was the dismissal of the Whitlam government in the constitutional crisis of 1975.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] In the Senate (the upper house), there are 76 senators: twelve each from the states and two each from the mainland territories (the Australian Capital Territory and the Northern Territory).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The House of Representatives (the lower house) has 150 members elected from single-member electoral divisions, commonly known as "electorates" or "seats", allocated to states on the basis of population, with each of the current states guaranteed a minimum of five seats.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The lower house has a maximum term of three years, but this is not fixed and governments usually dissolve the house early for an election at some point in the 6 months before the maximum.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Elections for both chambers are generally held simultaneously with senators having overlapping six-year terms except for those from the territories, whose terms are not fixed but are tied to the electoral cycle for the lower house.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Thus, only 40 of the 76 places in the Senate are put to each election unless the cycle is interrupted by a double dissolution.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia's electoral system uses preferential voting for the House of Representatives and all state and territory lower house elections (with the exception of Tasmania and the ACT which use the Hare-Clark system).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The Senate and most state upper houses use the proportional system which combines preferential voting with proportional representation for each state.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Voting and enrolment is compulsory for all enrolled citizens 18 years and older in every jurisdiction.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The party with majority support in the House of Representatives forms the government and its leader becomes prime minister.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The governor-general appoints the prime minister and may dismiss one who has lost the confidence of parliament or acts illegally.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] As Australia is a Westminster parliamentary democracy with a powerful and elected upper house, its system has sometimes been called a "Washminster mutation", or semi-parliamentary.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] There are two major political groups that have usually formed government federally: the Australian Labor Party and the Coalition which is a grouping of the Liberal Party and its minor partner, the National Party.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Within Australian political culture, the Labor Party is considered centre-left and the Coalition is considered centre-right.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Independent members and several minor parties have achieved representation in Australian parliaments, mostly in upper houses.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The Australian Greens have been the third largest party by both vote and membership since 2004.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia has six states – New South Wales (NSW), Victoria (Vic), Queensland (Qld), Western Australia (WA), South Australia (SA) and Tasmania (Tas) – and two mainland self-governing territories – the Australian Capital Territory (ACT) and the Northern Territory (NT).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The states have the general power to make laws except in the few areas where the constitution grants the Commonwealth (the federal level of government) exclusive powers.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The Commonwealth can only make laws on topics listed in the constitution but its laws prevail over those of the states to the extent of any inconsistency.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Since Federation, the Commonwealth's power relative to the states has significantly increased due to the increasingly wide interpretation given to listed Commonwealth powers – and because of the states' heavy financial reliance on Commonwealth grants.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Each state and major mainland territory has its own parliament – unicameral in the Northern Territory, the ACT and Queensland, and bicameral in the other states.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The lower houses are known as the Legislative Assembly (the House of Assembly in South Australia and Tasmania); the upper houses are known as the Legislative Council.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The head of the government in each state is the premier and in each territory the chief minister.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The King is represented in each state by a governor.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] At the Commonwealth level, the King's representative is the governor-general.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The remote Macquarie Island and Lord Howe Island are part of Tasmania and New South Wales respectively.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, whose foreign relations has three core bi-partisan pillars: commitment to the US alliance, engagement with the Indo-Pacific and support for international institutions, rules and co-operation.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Through the ANZUS pact and its status as a major non-NATO ally, Australia maintains a close relationship with the US, which encompasses strong defence, security and trade ties.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] In the Indo-Pacific, the country seeks to increase its trade ties through the open flow of trade and capital, while managing the rise of Chinese power by supporting the existing rules-based order.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Regionally, the country is a member of the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community, the ASEAN+6 mechanism and the East Asia Summit.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Internationally, the country is a member of the United Nations (of which it was a founding member), the Commonwealth of Nations, the OECD and the G20.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] This reflects the country's generally strong commitment to multilateralism.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia has pursued the cause of international trade liberalisation.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] It led the formation of the Cairns Group and Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, and is a member of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) and the World Trade Organization (WTO).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia maintains a deeply integrated relationship with neighbouring New Zealand, with free mobility of citizens between the two countries under the Trans-Tasman Travel Arrangement and free trade under the Closer Economic Relations agreement.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The most favourably viewed countries by the Australian people in 2021 include New Zealand, the United Kingdom, Japan, Germany, Taiwan, Thailand, the United States and South Korea.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] It also maintains an international aid program under which some 75 countries receive assistance.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia ranked fourth in the Center for Global Development's 2021 Commitment to Development Index.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The power over foreign policy is highly concentrated in the prime minister and the national security committee, with major decision such as joining the 2003 invasion of Iraq made without prior Cabinet approval.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Similarly, the Parliament does not play a formal role in foreign policy and the power to declare war lies solely with the executive government.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade supports the executive in its policy decisions.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The two main institutions involved in the management of Australia's armed forces are the Australian Defence Force (ADF) and the Department of Defence, together known as "Defence".
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The Australian Defence Force is the military wing, headed by the chief of the defence force, and contains three branches: the Royal Australian Navy, the Australian Army and the Royal Australian Air Force.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] In 2021, it had 84,865 currently serving personnel (including 60,286 regulars and 24,581 reservists).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The Department of Defence is the civilian wing and is headed by the secretary of defence.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] These two leaders collective manage Defence as a diarchy, with shared and joint responsibilities.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The titular role of commander-in-chief is held by the governor-general; however, actual command is vested in the chief of the Defence Force.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The executive branch of the Commonwealth government has overall control of the military through the minister of defence, who is subject to the decisions of Cabinet and its National Security Committee.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Major Australian intelligence agencies include the Australian Secret Intelligence Service (foreign intelligence), the Australian Signals Directorate (signals intelligence) and the Australian Security Intelligence Organisation (domestic security).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] In 2022, defence spending was 1.9% of GDP, representing the world's 13th-largest defence budget.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia has generally strong protections for civil and political rights, and the country has signed up to a wide range of international rights treaties.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Important documents protecting human rights include the Constitution, the *Racial Discrimination Act 1975*, the *Sex Discrimination Act 1984*, the *Disability Discrimination Act 1992*, and the *Age Discrimination Act 2004*.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Same-sex marriage has been legal in the nation since 2017.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Unlike other comparable Western democracies, Australia does not have a single federal charter of rights in the Constitution or under legislation; however, the ACT, Victoria, and Queensland have state-based ones.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] International organisations such as Human Rights Watch and Amnesty International have expressed concerns in areas including asylum-seeker policy, Indigenous deaths in custody, the lack of entrenched rights protection, and laws restricting protesting.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia's mixed-market economy is highly developed and rich in natural resources.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] It is the world's twelfth largest by nominal terms, and the twenty-third largest by PPP.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] As of 2021, Australia has the second-highest amount of wealth per adult, after Luxembourg, and the thirteenth-highest financial assets per capita, as well as one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] It has a labour force of some 13.5 million, with an unemployment rate of 3.5% as of June 2022.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] According to the Australian Council of Social Service, the poverty rate of Australia exceeds 13.6% of the population, encompassing over 3.2 million.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] It also estimated that there were 774,000 (17.7%) children under the age of 15 living in relative poverty.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The Australian dollar is the national currency, which is also used by three island states in the Pacific: Kiribati, Nauru, and Tuvalu.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australian government debt, about $963 billion in June 2022, exceeds 45.1% of the country's total GDP, and is the world's eighth-highest.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia had the second-highest level of household debt in the world in 2020, after Switzerland.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Its house prices are among the highest in the world, especially in the large urban areas.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The large service sector accounts for about 71.2% of total GDP, followed by the industrial sector (25.3%), while its agriculture sector makes up 3.6% of total GDP.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia is the world's 21st-largest exporter and 24th-largest importer.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] China is Australia's largest trading partner, accounting for roughly 40% of the country's exports and 17.6% of its imports.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Other major export markets include Japan, the United States, and South Korea.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia has high levels of competitiveness and economic freedom, and was ranked tenth in the Human Development Index in 2022.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] As of 2022, it is ranked twelfth in the Index of Economic Freedom.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] It attracted 9.5 million international tourists in 2019, and was ranked thirteenth among the countries of Asia-Pacific in 2019 for inbound tourism.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The 2021 *Travel and Tourism Competitiveness Report* ranked Australia seventh-highest in the world out of 117 countries.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Its international tourism receipts in 2019 amounted to $45.7 billion.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Total consumption of energy in this period was sourced from coal (28.4%), oil (37.3%), gas (27.4%) and renewables (7%).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] From 2012 to 2022, the energy sourced from renewables has increased 5.7%, while energy sourced from coal has decreased 2.6%.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] The use of gas also increased by 1.5% and the use of oil stayed relatively stable with a reduction of only 0.2%.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] In 2020, Australia produced 27.7% of its electricity from renewable sources, exceeding the target set by the Commonwealth government in 2009 of 20% renewable energy by 2020.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] A new target of 82% renewable energy by 2030 was set in 2022 and a target for net zero emissions by 2050 was set in 2021.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] In 2019, Australia spent $35.6 billion on research and development, allocating about 1.79% of GDP.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] A 2022 study by the industry lobby group, The Tech Council of Australia, stated that the Australian technology sector combined contributes $167 billion a year to the economy and employs 861,000 people.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] In 2022, startup ecosystems in Sydney and Melbourne were valued at $34 billion.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australia ranked 22nd in the Global Innovation Index 2025.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] With only 0.3% of the world's population, Australia contributed over 4% of the world's published research in 2020, making it one of the top 10 research contributors in the world.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] CSIRO, Australia's national science agency, contributes 10% of all research in the country, while the rest is carried out by universities.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Australian achievements include the invention of atomic absorption spectroscopy, the essential components of Wi-Fi technology, and the development of the first commercially successful polymer banknote.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] As of 2026, 14 Australian scientists have been awarded the Nobel Prize in physics, chemistry or medicine, and two have been awarded the Fields Medal.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p01] Facilities supporting space exploration include the Square Kilometre Array and Australia Telescope Compact Array radio telescopes, telescopes such as the Siding Spring Observatory, and ground stations such as the Canberra Deep Space Communication Complex.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] The population of Australia is estimated to be 27,724,744 as of September 2025.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] It is the 54th most populous country in the world and the most populous Oceanian country.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Australia has a population density of 3.4 persons per square kilometre of total land area, which makes it one of the most sparsely populated countries in the world.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] The population is heavily concentrated on the east coast, and in particular in the south-eastern region between South East Queensland to the north-east and Adelaide to the south-west.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Australia is also highly urbanised, with 67% of the population living in the Greater Capital City Statistical Areas (metropolitan areas of the state and mainland territorial capital cities) in 2018.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Metropolitan areas with more than one million inhabitants are Sydney, Melbourne, Brisbane, Perth and Adelaide.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] In common with many other developed countries, Australia is experiencing a demographic shift towards an older population, with more retirees and fewer people of working age.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] In 2021, the average age of the population was 39 years.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Australia has five cities (including their suburbs) that have populations larger than one million people.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] The majority of Australia's population lives near coastlines.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Between 1788 and the Second World War, the vast majority of settlers and immigrants came from the British Isles (principally England, Ireland and Scotland), although Australia had significant immigration from China and Germany during the 19th century.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Following Federation in 1901, the white Australia policy was strengthened, restricting further migration from these areas.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] However, this policy was relaxed following WW2, and in the decades following, Australia received a large wave of immigration from across Europe, with many more immigrants arriving from Southern and Eastern Europe than in previous decades.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Following the end of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia adopted multiculturalism as policy, culminating in the Racial Discrimination Act 1975.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Subsequently, there has been a large and continuing wave of immigration from across the world, with Asia being the largest source of immigrants in the 21st century.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Today, Australia has the world's eighth-largest immigrant population, with immigrants accounting for 30% of the population, the highest proportion among major Western nations.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] In 2022–23, 212,789 permanent migrants were admitted to Australia, with a net migration population gain of 518,000 people inclusive of non-permanent residents.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Most entered on skilled visas, however the immigration program also offers visas for family members and refugees.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] The Australian Bureau of Statistics asks each Australian resident to nominate up to two ancestries each census and the responses are classified into broad ancestry groups.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 3.8% of the Australian population identified as being Indigenous – Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] English has no legal status in Australia but it is the *de facto* official and national language due to its widespread established use.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Australian English is a major variety of the language with a distinctive accent and lexicon, and differs slightly from other varieties of English in grammar and spelling.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] General Australian serves as the standard dialect.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] The Australian sign language known as Auslan was used at home by 16,242 people at the time of the 2021 census.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, English was the only language spoken in the home for 72% of the population.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] The next most common languages spoken at home were Mandarin (2.7%), Arabic (1.4%), Vietnamese (1.3%), Cantonese (1.2%) and Punjabi (0.9%).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] More than 250 Australian Aboriginal languages are thought to have existed at the time of first European contact.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] The National Indigenous Languages Survey (NILS) for 2018–19 found that more than 120 Indigenous language varieties were in use or being revived, although 70 of those in use were endangered.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] The 2021 census found that 167 Indigenous languages were spoken at home by 76,978 Indigenous Australians – Yumplatok (Torres Strait Creole), Djambarrpuyngu (a Yolŋu language) and Pitjantjatjara (a Western Desert language) were among the most widely spoken.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] NILS and the Australian Bureau of Statistics use different classifications for Indigenous Australian languages.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Australia has no state religion; section 116 of the Australian Constitution prohibits federal legislation that would establish any religion, impose any religious observance, or prohibit the free exercise of any religion.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] However, the states still retain the power to pass religiously discriminatory laws.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 38.9% of the population identified as having no religion, up from 15.5% in 2001.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] The largest religion is Christianity (43.9% of the population).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] The largest Christian denominations are the Catholic Church (20% of the population) and the Anglican Church of Australia (9.8%).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Non-British immigration since the Second World War has led to the growth of non-Christian religions, the largest of which are Islam (3.2%), Hinduism (2.7%), Buddhism (2.4%), Sikhism (0.8%), and Judaism (0.4%).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] In 2021, just under 8,000 people declared an affiliation with traditional Aboriginal religions.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] In Australian Aboriginal mythology and the animist framework developed in Aboriginal Australia, the Dreaming is a sacred era in which ancestral totemic spirit beings formed The Creation.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] The Dreaming established the laws and structures of society and the ceremonies performed to ensure continuity of life and land.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Australia's life expectancy of 83 years (81 years for males and 85 years for females) is the fifth-highest in the world.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] It has the highest rate of skin cancer in the world, while cigarette smoking is the largest preventable cause of death and disease, responsible for 7.8% of the total mortality and disease.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Ranked second in preventable causes is hypertension at 7.6%, with obesity third at 7.5%.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Australia ranked 35th in the world in 2012 for its proportion of obese women and near the top of developed nations for its proportion of obese adults; 63% of its adult population is either overweight or obese.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Australia spent about 9.91% of its total GDP to health care in 2021.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] It introduced a national insurance scheme in 1975.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Following a period in which access to the scheme was restricted, the scheme became universal once more in 1981 under the name of Medicare.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] The program is nominally funded by an income tax surcharge known as the Medicare levy, currently at 2%.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] The states manage hospitals and attached outpatient services, while the Commonwealth funds the Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme (subsidising the costs of medicines) and general practice.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] School attendance, or registration for home schooling, is compulsory throughout Australia.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Education is primarily the responsibility of the individual states and territories; however, the Commonwealth has significant influence through funding agreements.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Since 2014, a national curriculum developed by the Commonwealth has been implemented by the states and territories.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Attendance rules vary between states, but in general children are required to attend school from the age of about 5 until about 16.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] In some states (Western Australia, Northern Territory and New South Wales), children aged 16–17 are required to either attend school or participate in vocational training, such as an apprenticeship.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] According to the 2022 PISA evaluations, Australian 15-year-olds ranked ninth in the OECD for reading and science and tenth for maths.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] However, less than 60% of Australian students achieved the National Proficiency Standard – 51% in maths, 58% in science and 57% in reading.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Australia has an adult literacy rate that was estimated to be 99% in 2003.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] However, a 2011–2012 report for the Australian Bureau of Statistics found that 44% of the population does not have high literary and numeracy competence levels, interpreted by others as suggesting that they do not have the "skills needed for everyday life".
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Australia has 37 government-funded universities and three private universities, as well as a number of other specialist institutions that provide approved courses at the higher education level.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] The OECD places Australia among the most expensive nations to attend university.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] There is a state-based system of vocational training, known as TAFE, and many trades conduct apprenticeships for training new tradespeople.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] About 58% of Australians aged from 25 to 64 have vocational or tertiary qualifications and the tertiary graduation rate of 49% is the highest among OECD countries.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] 38% of Australia's population has attained a higher education qualification, which is among the highest percentages in the world.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Australia has the highest ratio of international students per head of population in the world by a large margin, with 812,000 international students enrolled in the nation's universities and vocational institutions in 2019.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Accordingly, in 2019, international students represented on average 26.7% of the student bodies of Australian universities.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] International education therefore represents one of the country's largest exports and has a pronounced influence on the country's demographics, with a significant proportion of international students remaining in Australia after graduation on various skill and employment visas.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Education is Australia's third-largest export, after iron ore and coal, and contributed more than $28 billion to the economy in the 2016–17 financial year.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Contemporary Australian culture is diverse and reflects the country's Indigenous traditions, British and Irish heritage, and post-1945 history of multicultural immigration.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] The culture of the United States has also been influential.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] The evolution of Australian culture since British colonisation has given rise to distinctive cultural traits.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Many Australians identify egalitarianism, mateship, irreverence and a lack of formality as part of their national identity.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] These find expression in Australian slang, as well as Australian humour, which is often characterised as dry, irreverent and ironic.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] What these values mean, and whether Australians uphold them, has been debated since before Federation.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Australia has more than 100,000 Aboriginal rock art sites, and traditional designs, patterns and stories infuse contemporary Indigenous Australian art, "the last great art movement of the 20th century" according to critic Robert Hughes; its exponents include Emily Kame Kngwarreye.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Early colonial artists showed a fascination with the unfamiliar land.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] The impressionistic works of Arthur Streeton, Tom Roberts and other members of the 19th-century Heidelberg School – the first "distinctively Australian" movement in Western art – gave expression to nationalist sentiments in the lead-up to Federation.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] While the school remained influential into the 1900s, modernists such as Margaret Preston and Clarice Beckett, and, later, Sidney Nolan, explored new artistic trends.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] The landscape remained central to the work of Aboriginal watercolourist Albert Namatjira, as well as Fred Williams, Brett Whiteley and other post-war artists whose works, eclectic in style yet uniquely Australian, moved between the figurative and the abstract.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Australian literature grew slowly in the decades following European settlement though Indigenous oral traditions, many of which have since been recorded in writing, are much older.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] In the 19th century, Henry Lawson and Banjo Paterson captured the experience of the bush using a distinctive Australian vocabulary.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Their works are still popular; Paterson's bush poem "Waltzing Matilda" (1895) is regarded as Australia's unofficial national anthem.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Miles Franklin is the namesake of Australia's most prestigious literary prize, awarded annually to the best novel about Australian life.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Its first recipient, Patrick White, went on to win the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1973.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Australian Booker Prize winners include Peter Carey, Thomas Keneally and Richard Flanagan.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Australian public intellectuals have also written seminal works in their respective fields, including feminist Germaine Greer and philosopher Peter Singer.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] In the performing arts, Aboriginal peoples have traditions of religious and secular song, dance and rhythmic music often performed in corroborees.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] At the beginning of the 20th century, Nellie Melba was one of the world's leading opera singers, and later popular music acts such as the Bee Gees, AC/DC, INXS and Kylie Minogue achieved international recognition.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Many of Australia's performing arts companies receive funding through the Australian government's Australia Council.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] There is a symphony orchestra in each state, and a national opera company, Opera Australia, well known for its famous soprano Joan Sutherland.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Ballet and dance are represented by The Australian Ballet and various state companies.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Each state has a publicly funded theatre company.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Australia has two public broadcasters (the Australian Broadcasting Corporation and the multicultural Special Broadcasting Service), three commercial television networks, several pay-TV services, and numerous public, non-profit television and radio stations.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Each major city has at least one daily newspaper, and there are two national daily newspapers, *The Australian* and *The Australian Financial Review*.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] In 2024, Reporters Without Borders placed Australia 39th on a list of 180 countries ranked by press freedom, behind New Zealand (19th) and the United Kingdom (23rd), but ahead of the United States (55th).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] This relatively low ranking is primarily because of the limited diversity of commercial media ownership in Australia; most print media are under the control of News Corp Australia (59%) and Nine Entertainment (23%).
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Most Indigenous Australian groups subsisted on a diet of native fauna and flora, otherwise called bush tucker.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] It has increased in popularity among non-Indigenous Australians since the 1970s, with examples such as lemon myrtle, the macadamia nut and kangaroo meat now widely available.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] The first colonists introduced British and Irish cuisine to the continent.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] This influence is seen in dishes such as fish and chips, and in the Australian meat pie, which is related to the British steak pie.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Also during the colonial period, Chinese migrants paved the way for a distinctive Australian Chinese cuisine.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Post-war migrants transformed Australian cuisine, bringing with them their culinary traditions and contributing to new fusion dishes.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Italians introduced espresso coffee and, along with Greeks, helped develop Australia's café culture, of which the flat white and avocado toast are now considered Australian staples.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Pavlovas, lamingtons, Vegemite and Anzac biscuits are also often called iconic Australian foods.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Australia is a leading exporter and consumer of wine.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Australian wine is produced mainly in the southern, cooler parts of the country.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] The nation also ranks highly in beer consumption, with each state and territory hosting numerous breweries.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] The most popular sports in Australia by adult participation are: swimming, athletics, cycling, soccer, golf, tennis, basketball, surfing, netball and cricket.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Australia is one of five nations to have participated in every Summer Olympics of the modern era, and has hosted the Games twice: 1956 in Melbourne and 2000 in Sydney.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] It is also set to host the 2032 Games in Brisbane.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Australia has also participated in every Commonwealth Games, hosting the event in 1938, 1962, 1982, 2006 and 2018.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] The Australian national cricket team competed against England in both the first Test match (1877) and the first One Day International (1971), and against New Zealand in the first Twenty20 International (2004), winning all three games.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] It has also won the men's Cricket World Cup a record six times.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Australia has professional leagues for four football codes, whose relative popularity is divided geographically.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Originating in Melbourne in the 1850s, Australian rules football attracts the most television viewers in all states except New South Wales and Queensland, where rugby league holds sway, followed by rugby union.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] Soccer, while ranked fourth in television viewers and resources, has the highest overall participation rates.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] The surf lifesaving movement originated in Australia in the early 20th century, following the relaxation of laws prohibiting daylight bathing on Australian beaches.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australia-p02] The volunteer lifesaver is one of the country's icons.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australian-aborigines] Humans first migrated to Australia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, and over time formed as many as 500 linguistic and territorial groups.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australian-aborigines] Aboriginal people once lived across large areas of the continental shelf that were later inundated by postglacial sea-level rise at the start of the Holocene inter-glacial period, reshaping coastal landscapes and separating Tasmania from the mainland.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australian-aborigines] Aboriginal people maintained extensive networks within the continent and certain groups maintained relationships with Torres Strait Islanders and the Makassar people of modern-day Indonesia.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australian-aborigines] Over the millennia, Aboriginal people developed complex trade networks, inter-cultural relationships, law and religions, which make up some of the oldest continuous cultures in the world.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australian-aborigines] At the time of European colonisation of Australia, the Aboriginal people spoke more than 250 different languages, possessed varying degrees of technology, and lived in various types of settlements.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australian-aborigines] Languages (or dialects) and language-associated groups of people are connected with stretches of territory known as "Country", with which they have a profound spiritual connection.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australian-aborigines] Contemporary Aboriginal beliefs are shaped by traditional beliefs, the disruption of colonisation, religions brought to the continent by later migrants, and contemporary issues.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australian-aborigines] Just over half hold secular or other spiritual beliefs or no religious affiliation; about 40% are Christian; and about 1% adhere to a traditional Aboriginal religion.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australian-aborigines] Traditional cultural beliefs are passed down and shared through dancing, stories, songlines, and art that collectively weave an ontology of modern daily life and ancient creation known as the Dreaming.
[src:australian-football-harmony-cup/australian-aborigines] Studies of Aboriginal groups' genetic makeup are ongoing, but evidence suggests that they have genetic inheritance from ancient Asian peoples.
